00:03:34.000 --> 00:03:37.240
[Amit Varma]: Chitranshul, welcome to the scene and the unseen.

00:03:37.240 --> 00:03:38.240
[Amit Varma]: Thank you so much.

00:03:38.240 --> 00:03:43.000
[Amit Varma]: Tell me a little bit about yourself before we start talking about your book.

00:03:43.000 --> 00:03:46.920
[Amit Varma]: Like you know, you're a lawyer and now you've written this book, which is ostensibly a book

00:03:46.920 --> 00:03:51.000
[Amit Varma]: about law, but it's really a book of history and an excellent one at that.

00:03:51.000 --> 00:03:52.000
[Amit Varma]: So what's your background?

00:03:52.000 --> 00:03:53.000
[Amit Varma]: Where are you from?

00:03:53.000 --> 00:03:54.000
[Guest]: How did you become a lawyer?

00:03:54.000 --> 00:03:55.000
[Guest]: So I'm from Ranchi.

00:03:55.000 --> 00:03:56.000
[Guest]: It's a place in Jharkhand.

00:03:56.000 --> 00:04:00.440
[Guest]: MS Dhoni fame and from the same school.

00:04:00.440 --> 00:04:05.080
[Amit Varma]: So if someone says MS Dhoni should retire, is that seditious in Jharkhand?

00:04:05.080 --> 00:04:08.880
[Guest]: I really hope it becomes, those guys should be punished.

00:04:08.880 --> 00:04:09.880
[Guest]: Yeah.

00:04:09.880 --> 00:04:10.880
[Guest]: So I'm from Ranchi.

00:04:10.880 --> 00:04:12.360
[Guest]: I come from a background of science.

00:04:12.360 --> 00:04:19.520
[Guest]: I was not a arts or humanities student, but then law happened by accident and even history

00:04:19.520 --> 00:04:20.520
[Guest]: happened by accident.

00:04:20.520 --> 00:04:24.640
[Guest]: I hated history till I started reading it after college.

00:04:24.640 --> 00:04:29.260
[Guest]: So both accidental things combined into this book.

00:04:29.260 --> 00:04:32.280
[Guest]: So I studied law from Pune, Symbiosis Pune, five year course.

00:04:32.280 --> 00:04:37.240
[Guest]: Then I started practicing in 2009 and I'm an AOR of the Supreme Court and a partner

00:04:37.240 --> 00:04:39.640
[Guest]: with a pan-India law firm.

00:04:39.640 --> 00:04:42.440
[Guest]: And this is something I do on the side to keep myself happy.

00:04:42.440 --> 00:04:45.960
[Amit Varma]: And I guess when you start studying law, initially it's a subject.

00:04:45.960 --> 00:04:49.280
[Amit Varma]: So you're looking at the textbooks and you're studying law and it's the subjects and all

00:04:49.280 --> 00:04:51.640
[Amit Varma]: that, but it's much broader and deeper than that.

00:04:51.640 --> 00:04:53.160
[Amit Varma]: There are so many stories behind it.

00:04:53.160 --> 00:04:57.240
[Amit Varma]: And the history of law in a sense is a history of society and a history of people and all

00:04:57.240 --> 00:04:58.280
[Amit Varma]: of that.

00:04:58.280 --> 00:05:02.000
[Amit Varma]: At what point did you start to get interested in these sort of broader aspects?

00:05:02.000 --> 00:05:07.280
[Guest]: I would say in college, in college when we were studying jurisprudence and we were studying

00:05:07.280 --> 00:05:11.560
[Guest]: legal history, that's when I started understanding that you can't look at law in isolation.

00:05:11.560 --> 00:05:13.400
[Guest]: It doesn't operate in a vacuum.

00:05:13.400 --> 00:05:17.920
[Guest]: It has to do with what the society of that day is like.

00:05:17.920 --> 00:05:22.560
[Guest]: So you have to understand society and politics of the day to understand law.

00:05:22.560 --> 00:05:24.200
[Guest]: So you can't look at it in isolation.

00:05:24.200 --> 00:05:25.320
[Guest]: That's where I understood law.

00:05:25.320 --> 00:05:28.880
[Guest]: And then you start reading about world history and laws around the world.

00:05:28.880 --> 00:05:31.260
[Guest]: Then you understand how those things correlate with each other.

00:05:31.260 --> 00:05:37.360
[Amit Varma]: And what were the sort of great books on law or legal history that sort of influenced you?

00:05:37.360 --> 00:05:41.040
[Guest]: So I'll confess that there's no such book which influenced me.

00:05:41.040 --> 00:05:48.960
[Guest]: I would have actually not read legal history as a, because I really didn't like any, started

00:05:48.960 --> 00:05:51.200
[Guest]: some, I didn't like any other than maybe A.G.

00:05:51.200 --> 00:05:53.520
[Guest]: Noorani's great trials.

00:05:53.520 --> 00:05:58.600
[Guest]: Otherwise, I really didn't enjoy legal history books because they're very dry for my taste

00:05:58.600 --> 00:05:59.600
[Amit Varma]: at least.

00:05:59.600 --> 00:06:02.920
[Amit Varma]: That was an interesting sort of cautionary lesson you seem to have taken because your

00:06:02.920 --> 00:06:04.560
[Amit Varma]: book is anything but dry.

00:06:04.560 --> 00:06:08.120
[Amit Varma]: So what's the kind of stuff that you would read like intellectually, what makes you the

00:06:08.120 --> 00:06:09.120
[Amit Varma]: person you are?

00:06:09.120 --> 00:06:12.520
[Guest]: What are your sort of influences outside of law?

00:06:12.520 --> 00:06:13.520
[Guest]: Outside of law?

00:06:13.520 --> 00:06:14.520
[Guest]: I don't know.

00:06:14.520 --> 00:06:18.800
[Guest]: To be honest, I actually don't have an answer for this.

00:06:18.800 --> 00:06:20.880
[Guest]: So how did the book come about?

00:06:20.880 --> 00:06:21.880
[Guest]: So I was writing columns.

00:06:21.880 --> 00:06:27.120
[Guest]: There's this very good friend of mine, Rukun, who used to work with Penguin earlier.

00:06:27.120 --> 00:06:31.360
[Guest]: And she said she thought that I would write a book I never thought I would.

00:06:31.360 --> 00:06:34.960
[Guest]: And she connected me with Mansi, who's a commissioning editor at Penguin.

00:06:34.960 --> 00:06:37.360
[Guest]: And she sort of did an inception on me.

00:06:37.360 --> 00:06:40.080
[Guest]: She told me I should pick a topic to write on.

00:06:40.080 --> 00:06:41.240
[Guest]: And I gave her five options.

00:06:41.240 --> 00:06:42.560
[Guest]: She said, you should write on sedition.

00:06:42.560 --> 00:06:43.560
[Guest]: I said, Oh, should I?

00:06:43.560 --> 00:06:44.720
[Guest]: She said, yes, you should write on sedition.

00:06:44.720 --> 00:06:46.920
[Guest]: Now you pitch the idea to us.

00:06:46.920 --> 00:06:50.200
[Guest]: So then I thought about how to go about it.

00:06:50.200 --> 00:06:52.040
[Guest]: And then I created this structure for this book.

00:06:52.040 --> 00:06:53.760
[Guest]: And then they said, Oh, fine, we approve of your idea.

00:06:53.760 --> 00:06:57.160
[Guest]: So the idea was they themselves gave me the approval of the idea.

00:06:57.160 --> 00:06:58.520
[Guest]: And that's how that book happened.

00:06:58.520 --> 00:06:59.520
[Amit Varma]: That's very cunning.

00:06:59.520 --> 00:07:00.520
[Amit Varma]: What were the other four?

00:07:00.520 --> 00:07:03.680
[Guest]: So I was thinking about writing of these archaic laws, which is stupid.

00:07:03.680 --> 00:07:05.840
[Guest]: One of those laws were adultery laws.

00:07:05.840 --> 00:07:10.520
[Guest]: So all these Victorian laws, which shouldn't have existed in post independence India, I

00:07:10.520 --> 00:07:12.320
[Guest]: want to write about all those laws.

00:07:12.320 --> 00:07:14.000
[Amit Varma]: But she restricted me to this one law.

00:07:14.000 --> 00:07:15.000
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, adultery 377.

00:07:15.000 --> 00:07:18.920
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, I've in fact had episodes on.

00:07:18.920 --> 00:07:24.360
[Amit Varma]: So when you decided when they asked you to pitch your idea to them, I suppose you started

00:07:24.360 --> 00:07:26.200
[Amit Varma]: thinking about it a bit.

00:07:26.200 --> 00:07:28.840
[Amit Varma]: Was a book that you pitched to them similar to the one that you wrote?

00:07:28.840 --> 00:07:30.440
[Guest]: It's almost identical.

00:07:30.440 --> 00:07:31.440
[Guest]: It's almost identical.

00:07:31.440 --> 00:07:36.600
[Guest]: Maybe it grew a little more in scope, in the sense that I realized that the topic is too

00:07:36.600 --> 00:07:40.020
[Guest]: vast to restrict it to anything.

00:07:40.020 --> 00:07:42.560
[Guest]: So the general structure remained the same.

00:07:42.560 --> 00:07:46.740
[Guest]: But I added a little more bulk to the history part to the origin part.

00:07:46.740 --> 00:07:50.040
[Guest]: When I started writing, I did not realize that I would spend so much time on origin

00:07:50.040 --> 00:07:55.200
[Guest]: or so many chapters on origin and pre independence aspects of tradition law, but it really grew

00:07:55.200 --> 00:07:56.200
[Guest]: to a huge volume.

00:07:56.200 --> 00:08:00.200
[Guest]: So I actually had to control myself stop myself from writing further on it.

00:08:00.200 --> 00:08:04.080
[Amit Varma]: No, and I found that history part especially I mean, the book is a book of history and

00:08:04.080 --> 00:08:09.640
[Amit Varma]: I found it really fascinating because I learned stuff I didn't know about English law, how

00:08:09.640 --> 00:08:17.200
[Amit Varma]: it originated, about, you know, how it evolved in colonial times, and also all the sort of

00:08:17.200 --> 00:08:22.040
[Amit Varma]: the political and social context that you set to everything.

00:08:22.040 --> 00:08:25.960
[Amit Varma]: So once you I mean, the narrative you pitched, obviously, then is how the law has evolved

00:08:25.960 --> 00:08:28.360
[Amit Varma]: over the centuries and where we are now.

00:08:28.360 --> 00:08:32.800
[Amit Varma]: And at that point, you realized that okay, it's going to be a bit of a book of history.

00:08:32.800 --> 00:08:34.040
[Amit Varma]: Did you read a lot of history?

00:08:34.040 --> 00:08:38.440
[Guest]: I read history, but I did not read Indian history as much as I would have liked to.

00:08:38.440 --> 00:08:41.000
[Guest]: I usually read world history.

00:08:41.000 --> 00:08:45.160
[Guest]: And in fact, when I started writing this book, that's when I started looking at this more

00:08:45.160 --> 00:08:46.820
[Guest]: seriously.

00:08:46.820 --> 00:08:51.960
[Guest]: And I realized there's a lot which went behind, let's say the Indian Penal Code itself.

00:08:51.960 --> 00:08:55.880
[Guest]: So by while I was writing about sedition, I realized it's very important to write about

00:08:55.880 --> 00:09:00.880
[Guest]: the Penal Code first, because you will not understand the context of this section 124

00:09:00.880 --> 00:09:05.920
[Guest]: a which provides for the offense of sedition, unless you actually understand how the Indian

00:09:05.920 --> 00:09:08.140
[Guest]: Penal Code came about to be.

00:09:08.140 --> 00:09:13.440
[Guest]: And then when I started reading, to be very honest, I learned while I was researching,

00:09:13.440 --> 00:09:17.440
[Guest]: I did not know these things before I started writing the book.

00:09:17.440 --> 00:09:21.440
[Guest]: So I was educating myself and writing at the same time.

00:09:21.440 --> 00:09:27.480
[Guest]: And so when I was reading that, then I realized that the laws which were in place before my

00:09:27.480 --> 00:09:32.040
[Guest]: college draft court came in before the East India Company took complete control of Indian

00:09:32.040 --> 00:09:34.200
[Guest]: courts and everything.

00:09:34.200 --> 00:09:37.240
[Guest]: The laws were indigenous, there was no structure.

00:09:37.240 --> 00:09:41.320
[Guest]: They were Hindus laws, they were Mohammedan laws for criminal prosecutions, they use Mohammedan

00:09:41.320 --> 00:09:45.400
[Guest]: laws just modified a little bit to suit the Hindu subjects.

00:09:45.400 --> 00:09:49.760
[Guest]: So criminal laws, mostly Mohammedan and civil laws, mostly Hindu.

00:09:49.760 --> 00:09:55.880
[Guest]: So that the term code, which that Indian Penal Code, the term code is sort of a misnomer

00:09:55.880 --> 00:09:56.880
[Guest]: here.

00:09:56.880 --> 00:10:00.880
[Guest]: Code usually is a compilation of existing laws.

00:10:00.880 --> 00:10:02.800
[Guest]: It's like a compendium of laws.

00:10:02.800 --> 00:10:08.040
[Guest]: But there was no such law in India, there was no such compilation to be done in India.

00:10:08.040 --> 00:10:11.160
[Guest]: But so calling it a code as such is a misnomer.

00:10:11.160 --> 00:10:18.220
[Guest]: But if you consider India's past, as in that most of our laws are borrowed from the English

00:10:18.220 --> 00:10:19.560
[Guest]: common law system.

00:10:19.560 --> 00:10:23.080
[Guest]: And in that sense, yes, because it was part of the British Empire.

00:10:23.080 --> 00:10:27.800
[Guest]: So it was a code of laws, which were derived somewhat from the British Empire and then

00:10:27.800 --> 00:10:30.040
[Guest]: somewhat from indigenous laws.

00:10:30.040 --> 00:10:32.720
[Guest]: But in the true sense, it's not a code.

00:10:32.720 --> 00:10:37.800
[Guest]: So these are things which I actually learned when I was reading about how to pitch the

00:10:37.800 --> 00:10:38.800
[Guest]: book.

00:10:38.800 --> 00:10:40.600
[Amit Varma]: And then when I started writing the book,

00:10:40.600 --> 00:10:44.020
[Amit Varma]: And one of the like, whenever I read a book of history, one of the things that I keep

00:10:44.020 --> 00:10:48.720
[Amit Varma]: doing is I keep going to the footnotes and I get drawn into all these rabbit holes.

00:10:48.720 --> 00:10:53.080
[Amit Varma]: And the interesting thing I noticed in your footnotes is that, you know, a lot of the

00:10:53.080 --> 00:10:59.040
[Amit Varma]: sources are really arcane papers or arcane cases and not so much like I would have expected

00:10:59.040 --> 00:11:03.200
[Amit Varma]: that if you're doing a book of popular history, you'll, you know, all the standard historical

00:11:03.200 --> 00:11:04.960
[Amit Varma]: references will be there.

00:11:04.960 --> 00:11:07.560
[Amit Varma]: But your research kind of went a lot deeper than that.

00:11:07.560 --> 00:11:09.280
[Amit Varma]: So what was that process like?

00:11:09.280 --> 00:11:12.720
[Amit Varma]: And since you're not an academic, you're a working lawyer, you know, did you go time

00:11:12.720 --> 00:11:15.880
[Amit Varma]: to archives or libraries or did you affiliate yourself with an institution?

00:11:15.880 --> 00:11:18.360
[Amit Varma]: Or did you have to just work it all out on your own?

00:11:18.360 --> 00:11:20.960
[Guest]: So I had to work it all on my own.

00:11:20.960 --> 00:11:24.720
[Guest]: To be honest, I didn't go to the National Archives as other researchers or historians

00:11:24.720 --> 00:11:26.760
[Guest]: would go on the Nehru Memorial Library.

00:11:26.760 --> 00:11:30.120
[Guest]: I was constrained as far as time's concerned.

00:11:30.120 --> 00:11:33.040
[Guest]: And so I had to budget my time accordingly.

00:11:33.040 --> 00:11:37.720
[Guest]: So the resource that I use the most was archives that were achieved, which has absolutely everything

00:11:37.720 --> 00:11:41.080
[Guest]: in the world, you just need to know how to find it.

00:11:41.080 --> 00:11:43.880
[Guest]: So when I was researching, like you said, it's a rabbit hole.

00:11:43.880 --> 00:11:48.440
[Guest]: And that was the past I most enjoyed of the entire process.

00:11:48.440 --> 00:11:50.960
[Guest]: That was the part I most enjoyed.

00:11:50.960 --> 00:11:55.560
[Guest]: Going down that rabbit hole was very, very enjoyable, because you go to the most recent

00:11:55.560 --> 00:11:59.520
[Guest]: source, then you trace back to the source preceding that, then you trace back to that,

00:11:59.520 --> 00:12:03.320
[Guest]: beyond that, and then you suddenly realize that you're reading books from the 19th century,

00:12:03.320 --> 00:12:04.400
[Guest]: or the 18th century.

00:12:04.400 --> 00:12:09.440
[Guest]: And I've read texts from the 13th century and the 14th century in English, which I could

00:12:09.440 --> 00:12:11.360
[Guest]: barely understand.

00:12:11.360 --> 00:12:16.720
[Guest]: And that's when you realize that to write a book where people don't point fingers at

00:12:16.720 --> 00:12:19.080
[Guest]: you, you have to go to the origin.

00:12:19.080 --> 00:12:23.120
[Guest]: You can't rely on most recent history because history is colored by politics.

00:12:23.120 --> 00:12:25.480
[Guest]: History is colored by a person's bias.

00:12:25.480 --> 00:12:30.080
[Guest]: So you have to go to the source, the farthest you can go, you have to go there.

00:12:30.080 --> 00:12:32.040
[Amit Varma]: It's not easy, but you have to do it.

00:12:32.040 --> 00:12:36.400
[Amit Varma]: And just thinking about it strikes me as so mind blowing and so wonderful that, you know,

00:12:36.400 --> 00:12:40.160
[Amit Varma]: because of the internet, regular folks like you and I actually have a shot at going to

00:12:40.160 --> 00:12:43.360
[Amit Varma]: these basic primary older sources.

00:12:43.360 --> 00:12:47.600
[Amit Varma]: And you know, otherwise, to just get access to these kind of archives, you'd have to be

00:12:47.600 --> 00:12:50.560
[Amit Varma]: a professional historian and so on and so forth.

00:12:50.560 --> 00:12:54.160
[Amit Varma]: And now literally anyone can I mean, I'm obviously you know, when we were talking over coffee

00:12:54.160 --> 00:12:57.960
[Amit Varma]: before this, I recommended Dan Collins podcast, Hardcore History.

00:12:57.960 --> 00:12:59.920
[Amit Varma]: And you know, he was basically a radio broadcaster.

00:12:59.920 --> 00:13:01.520
[Amit Varma]: He wasn't a historian.

00:13:01.520 --> 00:13:05.200
[Amit Varma]: And yet he is able to produce these remarkable works of history because the world is at his

00:13:05.200 --> 00:13:06.200
[Guest]: fingertips.

00:13:06.200 --> 00:13:08.400
[Guest]: There are too many gatekeepers of knowledge today.

00:13:08.400 --> 00:13:13.040
[Guest]: Too many gatekeepers to just to enter the archives, you have to show your credentials

00:13:13.040 --> 00:13:17.040
[Guest]: that you're a researcher of some sort like a person like you or me can't just simply

00:13:17.040 --> 00:13:23.600
[Guest]: walk into it and say that I want to read something relating to the Mughal era or about Clive.

00:13:23.600 --> 00:13:26.280
[Guest]: I need to show them that yes, I'm a researcher for something.

00:13:26.280 --> 00:13:27.760
[Guest]: Otherwise, I can't go there.

00:13:27.760 --> 00:13:28.760
[Guest]: Why can't I go there?

00:13:28.760 --> 00:13:32.360
[Guest]: Why can't people like you and me go just walk in and learn?

00:13:32.360 --> 00:13:36.120
[Guest]: Because to be honest, the internet is a great resource and archives is an absolutely wonderful

00:13:36.120 --> 00:13:37.120
[Guest]: resource.

00:13:37.120 --> 00:13:40.880
[Guest]: And I so in fact, I while I was reading it, I felt so bad about using it so much that

00:13:40.880 --> 00:13:42.840
[Guest]: I actually started donating to it.

00:13:42.840 --> 00:13:44.120
[Guest]: And we have to do that.

00:13:44.120 --> 00:13:46.740
[Guest]: Otherwise, we won't get those resources.

00:13:46.740 --> 00:13:52.640
[Guest]: And even though it's a huge resource, still archives have certain things which you will

00:13:52.640 --> 00:13:57.400
[Guest]: not find in public, like the original draft penal code.

00:13:57.400 --> 00:14:01.200
[Guest]: When I was started writing the book, it took me four months to actually find it.

00:14:01.200 --> 00:14:02.360
[Guest]: And that to online.

00:14:02.360 --> 00:14:04.280
[Guest]: I don't know whether it's in some library or not.

00:14:04.280 --> 00:14:07.720
[Guest]: But all the people I talked to and I told them I have the original, I have the draft

00:14:07.720 --> 00:14:11.200
[Guest]: penal code of Macaulay's code of 1933 and 1937.

00:14:11.200 --> 00:14:13.040
[Guest]: And they said, How did you get it?

00:14:13.040 --> 00:14:14.040
[Guest]: People don't know it.

00:14:14.040 --> 00:14:15.440
[Guest]: People haven't read what's written there.

00:14:15.440 --> 00:14:17.680
[Guest]: They haven't seen his notes.

00:14:17.680 --> 00:14:20.160
[Guest]: And there are things like we know that Macaulay drafted it.

00:14:20.160 --> 00:14:24.680
[Guest]: But there's another person called Bethune, who also came up with a draft code.

00:14:24.680 --> 00:14:25.680
[Guest]: He hated Macaulay.

00:14:25.680 --> 00:14:27.160
[Guest]: He said, I want to do my own thing.

00:14:27.160 --> 00:14:32.720
[Guest]: And he paced this draft code to the East India Company, to the government then and he said,

00:14:32.720 --> 00:14:37.960
[Guest]: my code is better, but it was very conservative and very, the punishments were very draconian.

00:14:37.960 --> 00:14:39.600
[Guest]: So they eventually junked it.

00:14:39.600 --> 00:14:43.560
[Guest]: So before writing it, I did not know that such a draft code existed.

00:14:43.560 --> 00:14:45.080
[Guest]: Why don't we know this?

00:14:45.080 --> 00:14:48.380
[Guest]: Because we're not allowed to go into those places to learn about it.

00:14:48.380 --> 00:14:54.400
[Guest]: So we need open access, like archives helps, but we need open access to our libraries,

00:14:54.400 --> 00:14:55.400
[Guest]: all these archives.

00:14:55.400 --> 00:14:57.600
[Guest]: We do otherwise, it's not going to work.

00:14:57.600 --> 00:15:02.120
[Guest]: People are today, especially in today when people unlearn the history from WhatsApp and

00:15:02.120 --> 00:15:05.640
[Guest]: from social media, they need to go to these places to verify themselves.

00:15:05.640 --> 00:15:09.440
[Guest]: Otherwise, what they're relying on is again, bad information.

00:15:09.440 --> 00:15:12.800
[Amit Varma]: And I guess very newbie question, I guess in an ideal world, what all the archives and

00:15:12.800 --> 00:15:17.240
[Amit Varma]: all these repositories of documents should do is digitize everything put it up for free.

00:15:17.240 --> 00:15:21.000
[Amit Varma]: Absolutely. Is that kind of happening or are the gatekeepers holding first?

00:15:21.000 --> 00:15:25.880
[Guest]: See where the laws are beyond the copyright period, I think they can still be it's happening.

00:15:25.880 --> 00:15:29.040
[Guest]: But most people will see I still understand the author has to get the royalty and everyone

00:15:29.040 --> 00:15:31.280
[Guest]: has to be paid for what they published.

00:15:31.280 --> 00:15:38.360
[Guest]: But their articles like JSTOR is expensive for even for a person like me, I could not

00:15:38.360 --> 00:15:39.960
[Guest]: afford to have all those articles.

00:15:39.960 --> 00:15:43.360
[Guest]: So I used to rely on more four or five free articles a month.

00:15:43.360 --> 00:15:44.860
[Guest]: That's how bad it is.

00:15:44.860 --> 00:15:49.080
[Guest]: You have people who submit these papers, academic papers, and they themselves have to buy it

00:15:49.080 --> 00:15:50.080
[Guest]: back.

00:15:50.080 --> 00:15:51.840
[Guest]: They don't have access to even the PDFs.

00:15:51.840 --> 00:15:54.800
[Guest]: So even to get the PDFs, they have to buy it back.

00:15:54.800 --> 00:15:56.480
[Guest]: Why is it so expensive?

00:15:56.480 --> 00:15:59.560
[Guest]: A person who's himself written something, he should get free access to it, even he's

00:15:59.560 --> 00:16:01.440
[Guest]: not getting free access to it.

00:16:01.440 --> 00:16:05.240
[Guest]: So today, these things which if an author wants to put it out in public, he should be

00:16:05.240 --> 00:16:08.000
[Guest]: allowed to if he doesn't want to earn out of it.

00:16:08.000 --> 00:16:10.240
[Guest]: Fine, I understand the publishers put in money.

00:16:10.240 --> 00:16:13.480
[Guest]: But beyond a period of time, you should make this knowledge public.

00:16:13.480 --> 00:16:17.440
[Guest]: Otherwise, you're not going to learn otherwise, misinformation will keep spreading without

00:16:17.440 --> 00:16:18.440
[Guest]: verification.

00:16:18.440 --> 00:16:19.440
[Amit Varma]: Exactly.

00:16:19.440 --> 00:16:24.440
[Amit Varma]: And I mean, I'm not sure that making everything available does anything about misinformation,

00:16:24.440 --> 00:16:27.720
[Amit Varma]: because misinformation spreads because people want to be misinformed.

00:16:27.720 --> 00:16:28.720
[Amit Varma]: That's also true.

00:16:28.720 --> 00:16:34.960
[Amit Varma]: And because they're just lazy, and they want to read the latest slice of WhatsApp history.

00:16:34.960 --> 00:16:37.560
[Amit Varma]: Let's let's kind of go to your book now.

00:16:37.560 --> 00:16:43.720
[Amit Varma]: And your book really starts off with the East India Company coming to India.

00:16:43.720 --> 00:16:47.560
[Amit Varma]: And the interesting thing here, of course, is that there's no India as such there are

00:16:47.560 --> 00:16:51.240
[Amit Varma]: many different princely states, and they come as traders and they're given trading rights

00:16:51.240 --> 00:16:53.480
[Amit Varma]: and then negotiating their way through it.

00:16:53.480 --> 00:16:57.000
[Amit Varma]: And I found it pretty interesting how they are gradually trying to figure out what laws

00:16:57.000 --> 00:17:01.520
[Amit Varma]: apply to them, what laws apply to them for internal disputes, what laws apply to them

00:17:01.520 --> 00:17:06.180
[Amit Varma]: on ships and on the land, what you know, how do they, if there's a dispute between them

00:17:06.180 --> 00:17:08.000
[Amit Varma]: and locals, what happens?

00:17:08.000 --> 00:17:09.800
[Guest]: Can you sort of elaborate a bit on?

00:17:09.800 --> 00:17:10.800
[Guest]: Yes.

00:17:10.800 --> 00:17:13.360
[Guest]: So yes, when the East India Company came is very interesting, actually.

00:17:13.360 --> 00:17:16.960
[Guest]: So we used to keep reading about these factories that they had set up.

00:17:16.960 --> 00:17:18.880
[Guest]: So it's not a manufacturing factory.

00:17:18.880 --> 00:17:23.940
[Guest]: It's a place where East India Company's factors established the trade.

00:17:23.940 --> 00:17:28.760
[Guest]: Factors were people who would trade with the indigenous native traders, and then send some

00:17:28.760 --> 00:17:30.920
[Amit Varma]: back home and then bring stuff here.

00:17:30.920 --> 00:17:34.840
[Amit Varma]: So factors are basically like the agents like agents, the ship comes, it leaves the factors,

00:17:34.840 --> 00:17:37.720
[Amit Varma]: and negotiate, we will sell you this, we will buy this.

00:17:37.720 --> 00:17:39.720
[Guest]: Yes, they're like middlemen, mostly.

00:17:39.720 --> 00:17:41.760
[Guest]: And that's how the term factory comes in.

00:17:41.760 --> 00:17:45.640
[Guest]: Now that term where what they use a Surat factory and the Madras factory, that's how

00:17:45.640 --> 00:17:47.720
[Guest]: the term factory comes in.

00:17:47.720 --> 00:17:52.200
[Guest]: And when they got their factories, they realized that they have to fortify these factories.

00:17:52.200 --> 00:17:57.200
[Guest]: So they got their own militia, let's call them the militia, they are not like really

00:17:57.200 --> 00:18:01.000
[Guest]: British soldiers, they're militia, private mercenaries.

00:18:01.000 --> 00:18:05.480
[Guest]: So they got them, they set up these forts, and they set up their own communities.

00:18:05.480 --> 00:18:09.280
[Guest]: But the trouble was that there was life beyond these communities also, they would try life

00:18:09.280 --> 00:18:13.720
[Guest]: beyond these four walls, which was called referred to as a Mofasil.

00:18:13.720 --> 00:18:17.400
[Guest]: So that term still exists when we call when we talk about Mofasil towns, that small town

00:18:17.400 --> 00:18:23.840
[Guest]: in India, they use the term Mofasil to be places which are beyond these limits of these

00:18:23.840 --> 00:18:29.080
[Guest]: presidency towns, like beyond Bombay or beyond Madras, the presidency towns, I'm not talking

00:18:29.080 --> 00:18:31.960
[Guest]: about the region in general, I'm just talking about town.

00:18:31.960 --> 00:18:37.800
[Guest]: Even for example, Bombay, what you call town today, fort today was actually what the town

00:18:37.800 --> 00:18:40.880
[Guest]: of Bombay was beyond that it was not Bombay.

00:18:40.880 --> 00:18:42.200
[Amit Varma]: Similarly, it was Mofasil.

00:18:42.200 --> 00:18:45.960
[Guest]: Yes, Thane was Mofasil, Dadar was Mofasil.

00:18:45.960 --> 00:18:52.960
[Guest]: So even in Calcutta, the town was presidency controlled by the president of the factory.

00:18:52.960 --> 00:18:57.240
[Guest]: And anything beyond that, like Murshidabad, Hooghly, everything was Mofasil.

00:18:57.240 --> 00:19:03.960
[Guest]: So trouble started when there were disputes between Indians and the British or there were

00:19:03.960 --> 00:19:06.400
[Guest]: disputes amongst the British themselves.

00:19:06.400 --> 00:19:11.320
[Guest]: There was confusion that how what law should apply initially started with if someone did

00:19:11.320 --> 00:19:15.520
[Guest]: something some British citizen did something on a ship, then yes, a martial law could be

00:19:15.520 --> 00:19:16.520
[Guest]: applied.

00:19:16.520 --> 00:19:18.520
[Guest]: But what if he did something on land, what law would apply?

00:19:18.520 --> 00:19:20.080
[Guest]: So there was confusion.

00:19:20.080 --> 00:19:26.840
[Guest]: So there's a very interesting incident where the East India Company and the British courts,

00:19:26.840 --> 00:19:30.640
[Guest]: the presidency courts had a major conflict.

00:19:30.640 --> 00:19:36.520
[Guest]: And there was a zamindar who was being prosecuted by the British courts, like when I say British

00:19:36.520 --> 00:19:40.480
[Guest]: courts, not the East India Company courts, and was being protected by the company troops

00:19:40.480 --> 00:19:42.160
[Guest]: and the company courts.

00:19:42.160 --> 00:19:45.640
[Guest]: So then they realized they changed the law eventually.

00:19:45.640 --> 00:19:49.840
[Guest]: And they said that, okay, fine, if you are a British citizen, or there are disputes between

00:19:49.840 --> 00:19:54.400
[Guest]: two British citizens, then the British law would apply.

00:19:54.400 --> 00:19:59.520
[Guest]: But if you're an Indian citizen, and it's just something criminal in nature, then Nizami

00:19:59.520 --> 00:20:03.240
[Guest]: laws would apply, which is a leftover from the Mughals.

00:20:03.240 --> 00:20:06.840
[Guest]: So this actually continued till very, very late.

00:20:06.840 --> 00:20:11.160
[Guest]: This continued till I would say the latter part of the 19th century.

00:20:11.160 --> 00:20:15.320
[Amit Varma]: So it was all about even after the IPC was no after the IPC.

00:20:15.320 --> 00:20:17.440
[Guest]: So IPC only extended to presidency towns.

00:20:17.440 --> 00:20:20.800
[Guest]: So all these princely states and autonomous provinces had their own laws.

00:20:20.800 --> 00:20:21.800
[Guest]: The other had its own.

00:20:21.800 --> 00:20:27.720
[Guest]: Yeah, like, I don't know what other but Jammu and Kashmir, for example, the Ranbir Penal

00:20:27.720 --> 00:20:28.720
[Guest]: Code.

00:20:28.720 --> 00:20:34.960
[Guest]: It's till date, they have their own penal code, which I am assuming will go now.

00:20:34.960 --> 00:20:37.920
[Guest]: So they had their own systems and all such as in place.

00:20:37.920 --> 00:20:43.240
[Amit Varma]: Like you mentioned about how eventually, the East India Company evolved to a status where

00:20:43.240 --> 00:20:47.840
[Amit Varma]: they looked after what you call the Diwani rights, which is a civil justice system, the

00:20:47.840 --> 00:20:52.320
[Amit Varma]: revenue rights and the Nizami or the criminal justice powers remained with the Nizam and

00:20:52.320 --> 00:20:53.320
[Amit Varma]: his administrators.

00:20:53.320 --> 00:20:58.480
[Amit Varma]: Another very interesting part of the book was as far as local laws are concerned, how

00:20:58.480 --> 00:21:04.160
[Amit Varma]: the locals were sort of administered was that as far as civil laws or personal laws are

00:21:04.160 --> 00:21:07.280
[Amit Varma]: concerned depends on you know, the Hindus had their own thing, the Muslims have their

00:21:07.280 --> 00:21:08.280
[Unknown]: own thing.

00:21:08.280 --> 00:21:12.240
[Amit Varma]: But as far as a criminal justice system was concerned, it was a Mohammedan law which sort

00:21:12.240 --> 00:21:13.240
[Guest]: of applied.

00:21:13.240 --> 00:21:17.280
[Guest]: Yes, but that was true for the natives, not for British subjects.

00:21:17.280 --> 00:21:21.520
[Guest]: If there was a British subject under prosecution, he had to be prosecuted by a presidency court,

00:21:21.520 --> 00:21:25.800
[Guest]: or if a company could prosecuted him, then it had to be done according to British laws.

00:21:25.800 --> 00:21:28.320
[Amit Varma]: So how did sort of then these laws evolve?

00:21:28.320 --> 00:21:32.080
[Amit Varma]: So initially, the East India Company comes, they're only traders, they've got factors

00:21:32.080 --> 00:21:36.440
[Amit Varma]: in there, these factors and eventually the you know, factories are made, the militia

00:21:36.440 --> 00:21:41.000
[Amit Varma]: comes in to look after them, you have these towns coming, the presidency is coming up

00:21:41.000 --> 00:21:42.440
[Amit Varma]: with the Mofasil around them.

00:21:42.440 --> 00:21:43.440
[Amit Varma]: How are the laws evolving?

00:21:43.440 --> 00:21:46.840
[Amit Varma]: Initially, it's okay, if there's a dispute between two British guys, the British laws

00:21:46.840 --> 00:21:49.080
[Amit Varma]: apply if it's on a ship, it's martial law.

00:21:49.080 --> 00:21:52.800
[Amit Varma]: But then eventually you become a part of the local society which had has its own thing

00:21:52.800 --> 00:21:57.760
[Amit Varma]: going on where, you know, they have their own criminal laws, their own whatever, through

00:21:57.760 --> 00:22:01.520
[Amit Varma]: the period that the East India Company was here until the IPC, the IPC, of course, came

00:22:01.520 --> 00:22:02.520
[Amit Varma]: 1861, I think.

00:22:02.520 --> 00:22:03.520
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, IPC was 1860.

00:22:03.520 --> 00:22:04.520
[Guest]: Yeah.

00:22:04.520 --> 00:22:11.000
[Amit Varma]: So until that point in time, how has it evolved in the centuries before that?

00:22:11.000 --> 00:22:16.160
[Guest]: So there were laws, it's not as if they did not have specific statutes, even in areas

00:22:16.160 --> 00:22:18.640
[Guest]: controlled by the company, they had certain laws.

00:22:18.640 --> 00:22:21.920
[Guest]: So there were regulations, there were things called the Bombay regulations, there were

00:22:21.920 --> 00:22:25.000
[Guest]: things called the Madras regulations and Bengal regulations.

00:22:25.000 --> 00:22:29.640
[Guest]: For criminal law, Bengal regulations were mostly used even in Bombay and Madras for

00:22:29.640 --> 00:22:32.240
[Guest]: criminal prosecutions and criminal justice system.

00:22:32.240 --> 00:22:36.680
[Guest]: So they had regulations, they had some random laws for certain things.

00:22:36.680 --> 00:22:39.440
[Guest]: So it's not as if they did not have any laws.

00:22:39.440 --> 00:22:43.840
[Guest]: They had these statutes, which were typically derived from British laws, the common law

00:22:43.840 --> 00:22:49.720
[Guest]: system, because England does not have a typical legal system where everything is in the books.

00:22:49.720 --> 00:22:56.080
[Guest]: It evolves from the law of the courts, a court decides something, it becomes a law.

00:22:56.080 --> 00:23:00.560
[Guest]: It's not the other way around that, like in India, the statute dictates what the court

00:23:00.560 --> 00:23:01.560
[Guest]: can do.

00:23:01.560 --> 00:23:03.760
[Guest]: But in England, the courts dictated what the law became.

00:23:03.760 --> 00:23:05.800
[Amit Varma]: It's what you call the common law system.

00:23:05.800 --> 00:23:06.800
[Amit Varma]: Common law system.

00:23:06.800 --> 00:23:10.720
[Guest]: So there's no origin document as such, it just evolves over a period of time.

00:23:10.720 --> 00:23:14.120
[Guest]: Yes, so but there were laws, there were these regulations, which kept getting modified from

00:23:14.120 --> 00:23:17.500
[Guest]: time to time to suit the need of the hour.

00:23:17.500 --> 00:23:21.920
[Guest]: So it's not as if they did not have anything, they had laws, but yeah, it was not uniform

00:23:21.920 --> 00:23:22.920
[Guest]: across the country.

00:23:22.920 --> 00:23:29.680
[Guest]: So for example, in the Calcutta presidency, Bengal presidency, the punishment for forgery

00:23:29.680 --> 00:23:31.280
[Guest]: was death.

00:23:31.280 --> 00:23:36.840
[Guest]: Similarly, and for example, if you steal one rupee and the punishment is 10 years, stealing

00:23:36.840 --> 00:23:39.800
[Guest]: 1000 rupees also 10 years, stealing 1 lakh is also 10 years.

00:23:39.800 --> 00:23:42.000
[Guest]: So it's it was not proportionate at all.

00:23:42.000 --> 00:23:44.880
[Guest]: So that is something which Macaulay also wanted to reform.

00:23:44.880 --> 00:23:49.860
[Guest]: He points out that these laws number one that for the same offense, there's no proportionality

00:23:49.860 --> 00:23:52.380
[Guest]: with regard to the gravity of the offense.

00:23:52.380 --> 00:23:57.440
[Guest]: Then there are certain offenses which disturbed the local populations view.

00:23:57.440 --> 00:24:02.440
[Guest]: So basically, it's something which even today, religious law or a customary law, you may

00:24:02.440 --> 00:24:07.000
[Guest]: feel that no, it's necessary to have such a law like Sati when Sati was being banned,

00:24:07.000 --> 00:24:14.880
[Guest]: it led to a huge uproar when the age of consent to have intercourse was raised from 10 to

00:24:14.880 --> 00:24:15.880
[Guest]: 12.

00:24:15.880 --> 00:24:19.520
[Guest]: It led to the first sedition trial in 1891.

00:24:19.520 --> 00:24:24.000
[Guest]: So even people at that point of time, there were major discrepancies.

00:24:24.000 --> 00:24:28.240
[Amit Varma]: Like one of the interesting cases that you've written about in your book is King versus

00:24:28.240 --> 00:24:32.480
[Amit Varma]: Maharaja Nand Kumar, yes, which is his root called Nand Kumar, who gets into this sort

00:24:32.480 --> 00:24:35.000
[Amit Varma]: of ego battle with Warren Hastings.

00:24:35.000 --> 00:24:36.680
[Guest]: Tell me a bit about how that panned out.

00:24:36.680 --> 00:24:39.560
[Guest]: So it's been referred to as a judicial murder in history.

00:24:39.560 --> 00:24:41.440
[Guest]: It's been referred to as judicial murder.

00:24:41.440 --> 00:24:47.480
[Guest]: The Chief Justice of the Calcutta High Court was Elijah M. Pei and him and Hastings were

00:24:47.480 --> 00:24:49.480
[Guest]: buddies.

00:24:49.480 --> 00:24:56.440
[Guest]: And Nand Kumar was a native who rose to a status of a Diwan and was referred to as Raja

00:24:56.440 --> 00:24:59.120
[Guest]: and he became very rich.

00:24:59.120 --> 00:25:02.560
[Guest]: And he made allegations against Hastings, corruption allegations against Hastings, which

00:25:02.560 --> 00:25:03.560
[Guest]: was absolutely true.

00:25:03.560 --> 00:25:05.720
[Guest]: At that point of time, it was true.

00:25:05.720 --> 00:25:12.440
[Guest]: But to cut him to size, Hastings and M. Pei colluded and they accused him of forgery.

00:25:12.440 --> 00:25:14.920
[Guest]: And like I said, forgery was punishable with death.

00:25:14.920 --> 00:25:17.800
[Guest]: So they got together and it was a farce of a trial.

00:25:17.800 --> 00:25:19.960
[Guest]: He did not receive proper legal representation.

00:25:19.960 --> 00:25:25.440
[Guest]: He did not allow the proper lawyers or he was not allowed to plead his case properly.

00:25:25.440 --> 00:25:28.280
[Guest]: The evidence was murky at best.

00:25:28.280 --> 00:25:31.480
[Guest]: And they got together to kill him.

00:25:31.480 --> 00:25:34.960
[Guest]: To be honest, if I can just put it that way, they got together to kill him.

00:25:34.960 --> 00:25:38.720
[Guest]: I mean, he was convicted for forgery and he was sentenced to death.

00:25:38.720 --> 00:25:41.760
[Guest]: It was referred to as a judicial murder, which raised uproar even back in London.

00:25:41.760 --> 00:25:43.960
[Guest]: The parliament talked about it.

00:25:43.960 --> 00:25:49.560
[Guest]: Even in India, there was this popular sympathy for Nand Kumar for what he was going through.

00:25:49.560 --> 00:25:52.440
[Guest]: And actually showed at that point of time that there was a technical aspect involved

00:25:52.440 --> 00:25:55.880
[Guest]: within Nand Kumar could be even tried under British laws.

00:25:55.880 --> 00:25:59.360
[Guest]: Because like I said, he was a native who did not live in Calcutta.

00:25:59.360 --> 00:26:01.720
[Guest]: He was from Murshidabad.

00:26:01.720 --> 00:26:05.360
[Guest]: And the British law did not apply to the natives of Murshidabad.

00:26:05.360 --> 00:26:09.040
[Guest]: So what they did was they arrested him in Calcutta.

00:26:09.040 --> 00:26:15.360
[Guest]: And they tried him under British laws under these tyrannical laws.

00:26:15.360 --> 00:26:21.040
[Guest]: And as a result, a lot of natives left the presidency town.

00:26:21.040 --> 00:26:25.520
[Guest]: They just ran to these Mufsul towns, because they thought that even for a minor crime,

00:26:25.520 --> 00:26:27.080
[Guest]: they could be executed.

00:26:27.080 --> 00:26:30.520
[Amit Varma]: So there was an exodus from Calcutta after Nand Kumar's case.

00:26:30.520 --> 00:26:34.360
[Amit Varma]: And since it was being discussed in parliament and Hastings, of course, was very controversial

00:26:34.360 --> 00:26:35.360
[Unknown]: back home.

00:26:35.360 --> 00:26:37.120
[Amit Varma]: So eventually impeached eventually impeached.

00:26:37.120 --> 00:26:44.240
[Amit Varma]: Was there a sort of one did it lead to a great rise in disaffection among the local people?

00:26:44.240 --> 00:26:47.880
[Amit Varma]: And to did the British themselves feel that, hey, we got to, you know, chill out a bit

00:26:47.880 --> 00:26:49.840
[Guest]: and get this under control.

00:26:49.840 --> 00:26:56.160
[Guest]: So Hastings and MP, they were instrumentalities of the British crown, the East India Company

00:26:56.160 --> 00:27:00.500
[Guest]: as such the other officers of the East India Company were more sympathetic to Nand Kumar.

00:27:00.500 --> 00:27:06.040
[Guest]: So in fact, there was a huge conflict between company officers and these British instrumentalities.

00:27:06.040 --> 00:27:12.160
[Guest]: Now, when that happened, they actually did realize that there was an exodus of the natives

00:27:12.160 --> 00:27:15.880
[Amit Varma]: from Calcutta from Calcutta to Mufsul places.

00:27:15.880 --> 00:27:19.320
[Guest]: So they realize that and when they when they go out people stopping revenue when if they

00:27:19.320 --> 00:27:22.680
[Guest]: don't like you, they would rather pick up arms rather than pay revenue to you.

00:27:22.680 --> 00:27:25.840
[Guest]: And they relied on that revenue, they relied on trade.

00:27:25.840 --> 00:27:29.680
[Guest]: So a message was sent that this shouldn't have been done.

00:27:29.680 --> 00:27:33.080
[Guest]: A message was sent across Hastings was eventually recalled.

00:27:33.080 --> 00:27:35.680
[Guest]: So yes, there were definitely was conflict.

00:27:35.680 --> 00:27:38.440
[Guest]: And it did subsist for some time.

00:27:38.440 --> 00:27:42.680
[Guest]: But at the end of the day, there was no India as such then.

00:27:42.680 --> 00:27:44.100
[Guest]: So there was no unity as such.

00:27:44.100 --> 00:27:48.520
[Guest]: So it was more like a dispute between Nand Kumar and the crown than anything else.

00:27:48.520 --> 00:27:50.240
[Guest]: So people eventually got around.

00:27:50.240 --> 00:27:51.240
[Amit Varma]: Yeah.

00:27:51.240 --> 00:27:53.400
[Unknown]: So it's just, you know, new cycles.

00:27:53.400 --> 00:27:58.440
[Unknown]: Just like today, people move on to outrage about something else.

00:27:58.440 --> 00:28:03.600
[Amit Varma]: Let's let's kind of, you know, before we sort of dive into the 19th century in India and

00:28:03.600 --> 00:28:07.960
[Amit Varma]: the birth of the IPC, let's, you know, you have a chapter in your book about Bentham

00:28:07.960 --> 00:28:11.960
[Amit Varma]: Mill and Macaulay and the impact that they had on British law, especially Bentham and

00:28:11.960 --> 00:28:14.040
[Amit Varma]: his impact on British law.

00:28:14.040 --> 00:28:18.080
[Amit Varma]: Now, you've spoken about English law, and you've spoken about English law as basically

00:28:18.080 --> 00:28:22.160
[Amit Varma]: something that has evolved through this process of spontaneous order and has come down through

00:28:22.160 --> 00:28:24.080
[Amit Varma]: the years, a common law system.

00:28:24.080 --> 00:28:27.720
[Amit Varma]: And then, but Bentham is a seminal figure and how it evolves.

00:28:27.720 --> 00:28:29.400
[Amit Varma]: Tell me a little bit about that.

00:28:29.400 --> 00:28:33.480
[Guest]: So Bentham is a person who is responsible for the term codification.

00:28:33.480 --> 00:28:35.720
[Guest]: So in fact, let me correct you there.

00:28:35.720 --> 00:28:41.200
[Guest]: Bentham did not have that big an influence on English laws than he had on other countries

00:28:41.200 --> 00:28:43.720
[Guest]: laws, mostly on French law.

00:28:43.720 --> 00:28:48.600
[Guest]: He had a huge influence on French law, then that which extended to the colony of Louisiana

00:28:48.600 --> 00:28:52.240
[Guest]: and America, which was governed by the French back then.

00:28:52.240 --> 00:28:57.600
[Guest]: So his influence actually was more on French and Indian law than English law because the

00:28:57.600 --> 00:28:59.800
[Guest]: English still don't have a criminal code.

00:28:59.800 --> 00:29:03.360
[Amit Varma]: In fact, there's an interesting quote in your book about how Bentham saying that he's a

00:29:03.360 --> 00:29:06.360
[Amit Varma]: royalist in England, but a Republican in France.

00:29:06.360 --> 00:29:09.280
[Guest]: So Bentham lived through the revolution there.

00:29:09.280 --> 00:29:11.920
[Guest]: So Bentham is a very interesting character.

00:29:11.920 --> 00:29:14.680
[Guest]: Bentham opposed, he was a rebel of the day.

00:29:14.680 --> 00:29:18.480
[Guest]: He was not like a glamorous rebel, but he was a intellectual rebel.

00:29:18.480 --> 00:29:20.920
[Guest]: There was this gentleman called Blackstone.

00:29:20.920 --> 00:29:24.980
[Guest]: We still read Blackstone's law dictionary in India and everywhere across the world.

00:29:24.980 --> 00:29:29.720
[Guest]: So Blackstone was considered an authoritative figure on criminal law and Bentham completely

00:29:29.720 --> 00:29:31.800
[Guest]: disagreed with him.

00:29:31.800 --> 00:29:37.160
[Guest]: And he said that I would, he actually said things like, I want to burn the statutes of

00:29:37.160 --> 00:29:38.160
[Guest]: England.

00:29:38.160 --> 00:29:40.800
[Guest]: I want to burn this law down and build something new.

00:29:40.800 --> 00:29:44.480
[Guest]: And he did not find popular acceptance in England.

00:29:44.480 --> 00:29:49.480
[Guest]: So he actually went to France, he was depressed, he went to France and he built on that, his

00:29:49.480 --> 00:29:54.400
[Guest]: philosophy there, like for the greatest, the greater good for everyone, the greater utilitarian

00:29:54.400 --> 00:29:55.840
[Guest]: philosophy.

00:29:55.840 --> 00:29:57.600
[Guest]: And that's where codification began.

00:29:57.600 --> 00:30:02.240
[Guest]: Bentham himself wasn't very successful, if I can say so, but his followers, his disciples

00:30:02.240 --> 00:30:03.640
[Guest]: are more successful than him.

00:30:03.640 --> 00:30:06.280
[Guest]: Because they actually put this to work.

00:30:06.280 --> 00:30:12.080
[Guest]: Like Mill was a Bentham follower, Macaulay not so much, even though he does borrow from

00:30:12.080 --> 00:30:16.320
[Guest]: Bentham, but he was not like a Benthamite as much as Mill was.

00:30:16.320 --> 00:30:22.200
[Guest]: But eventually the system of codification was something which Bentham envisaged.

00:30:22.200 --> 00:30:25.320
[Guest]: And today we are actually having the benefit of that.

00:30:25.320 --> 00:30:27.520
[Amit Varma]: So what's the rationale behind codification?

00:30:27.520 --> 00:30:33.680
[Amit Varma]: Like why did Bentham feel that he wanted to burn all that there was before and that codification

00:30:33.680 --> 00:30:38.460
[Amit Varma]: was, I mean, you spoke of burning and there's an aside that in 1953, Ambedkar said that

00:30:38.460 --> 00:30:41.760
[Amit Varma]: looking at what the constitution has become today, I feel like burning it.

00:30:41.760 --> 00:30:42.760
[Amit Varma]: Yes.

00:30:42.760 --> 00:30:47.440
[Amit Varma]: But which is completely unrelated to all of this and not seditious in the least.

00:30:47.440 --> 00:30:52.840
[Amit Varma]: So to get back to my question about Bentham, what was it about law as it then was in England

00:30:52.840 --> 00:30:55.240
[Amit Varma]: that he wanted to burn and what was the necessity?

00:30:55.240 --> 00:30:57.880
[Amit Varma]: What was the rationale for needing to codify something?

00:30:57.880 --> 00:31:01.360
[Guest]: So if laws are not codified, it leads to confusion.

00:31:01.360 --> 00:31:02.360
[Guest]: It leads to uncertainty.

00:31:02.360 --> 00:31:05.000
[Guest]: We are lucky we got the IPC.

00:31:05.000 --> 00:31:06.000
[Guest]: I am saying so.

00:31:06.000 --> 00:31:07.000
[Guest]: We are very lucky we got the IPC.

00:31:07.000 --> 00:31:09.880
[Guest]: It's a great gift from the English to us.

00:31:09.880 --> 00:31:14.360
[Guest]: In the sense of the concept of codification, what the code itself is, you can debate.

00:31:14.360 --> 00:31:15.360
[Guest]: Correct.

00:31:15.360 --> 00:31:19.920
[Guest]: The concept of codification was excellent for India because we are very diverse.

00:31:19.920 --> 00:31:23.000
[Guest]: We had different traditions, customs across the country.

00:31:23.000 --> 00:31:25.880
[Guest]: Like I said, indigenous laws are completely different.

00:31:25.880 --> 00:31:30.120
[Guest]: Someone in the kingdom of Travancore or Mysore might have something completely different

00:31:30.120 --> 00:31:34.440
[Guest]: for Thaib, which may be different in the central provinces.

00:31:34.440 --> 00:31:39.200
[Guest]: And there are certain things, maybe offenses in one part, not an offense in another part.

00:31:39.200 --> 00:31:44.880
[Guest]: So it was very important to have a uniform system of penal law.

00:31:44.880 --> 00:31:48.320
[Guest]: Everyone needed to be on the same page where they knew what they can do and what they could

00:31:48.320 --> 00:31:49.680
[Guest]: not do.

00:31:49.680 --> 00:31:51.440
[Guest]: That is where codification becomes important.

00:31:51.440 --> 00:31:55.680
[Guest]: Without a code, you would have 100 different statutes in 100 different parts.

00:31:55.680 --> 00:31:59.000
[Guest]: And then there's some overlap, then there's confusion.

00:31:59.000 --> 00:32:03.000
[Guest]: So at the end of the day, for certainty in law, you need a code.

00:32:03.000 --> 00:32:08.200
[Guest]: So India has the civil procedure code, the criminal procedure code, which the criminal

00:32:08.200 --> 00:32:13.520
[Guest]: procedure code came later after the IPC was enacted and CPC also came later.

00:32:13.520 --> 00:32:19.040
[Guest]: But at the end of the day, these codes have had a major impact or rather they've shaped

00:32:19.040 --> 00:32:20.640
[Guest]: the Indian judicial system.

00:32:20.640 --> 00:32:24.800
[Guest]: Procedure is derived from the criminal procedure and the civil procedure codes.

00:32:24.800 --> 00:32:26.520
[Guest]: Penal offenses are derived from the IPC.

00:32:26.520 --> 00:32:30.680
[Guest]: Now we have penal offenses, other statutes as well, but there's no overlap in many cases.

00:32:30.680 --> 00:32:31.680
[Guest]: Most cases there's no overlap.

00:32:31.680 --> 00:32:36.320
[Guest]: In certain cases, there may be overlap, but then they're very, very specific in nature.

00:32:36.320 --> 00:32:39.600
[Guest]: Like you were just discussing about the UAPA and IPC.

00:32:39.600 --> 00:32:43.200
[Guest]: Like UAPA is very specific in nature.

00:32:43.200 --> 00:32:46.640
[Guest]: That's why as opposed to 124, which is general in nature.

00:32:46.640 --> 00:32:52.360
[Guest]: So but at the end of the day, mostly we have certainty, which was how a code becomes helpful

00:32:52.360 --> 00:32:54.520
[Amit Varma]: in India or anywhere else.

00:32:54.520 --> 00:32:58.120
[Amit Varma]: So essentially, you're saying the importance of a code basically is that the rule of law

00:32:58.120 --> 00:33:01.120
[Amit Varma]: needs to be both transparent and accountable and predictable.

00:33:01.120 --> 00:33:04.560
[Amit Varma]: And once you have a specific code out there, everyone knows what the rules of the game

00:33:04.560 --> 00:33:05.560
[Amit Varma]: are.

00:33:05.560 --> 00:33:06.560
[Guest]: Yes.

00:33:06.560 --> 00:33:07.560
[Guest]: But England doesn't have a code.

00:33:07.560 --> 00:33:10.800
[Guest]: Yes, England doesn't have a code and they suffered because of it for a very long time.

00:33:10.800 --> 00:33:13.920
[Guest]: There was a lot of confusion because of common law.

00:33:13.920 --> 00:33:16.040
[Guest]: I don't consider myself an authority on that.

00:33:16.040 --> 00:33:21.040
[Guest]: But broadly from what I've researched, there was no certain consistency in law, which they

00:33:21.040 --> 00:33:25.880
[Guest]: have remediated to a certain extent now, because earlier there were no statutes as such also.

00:33:25.880 --> 00:33:29.000
[Guest]: Now there are specific statutes for certain things.

00:33:29.000 --> 00:33:33.040
[Guest]: At the end of the day, like a money laundering or a bribery has a separate statute, money

00:33:33.040 --> 00:33:36.640
[Guest]: laundering has a separate statute, offense against the state has a separate statute.

00:33:36.640 --> 00:33:40.360
[Guest]: So they have these separate statutes for these specific laws, but they haven't brought it

00:33:40.360 --> 00:33:41.360
[Guest]: together.

00:33:41.360 --> 00:33:42.360
[Amit Varma]: Right.

00:33:42.360 --> 00:33:43.960
[Amit Varma]: Let's sort of get back to Bentham.

00:33:43.960 --> 00:33:47.080
[Amit Varma]: And, you know, one of his protégés was James Mill.

00:33:47.080 --> 00:33:50.960
[Amit Varma]: And as you point out, you know, through his 40s, and then gradually as he turns 50, he

00:33:50.960 --> 00:33:55.480
[Amit Varma]: becomes sort of the, you know, one of the key bureaucrats in charge of India who sort

00:33:55.480 --> 00:33:58.080
[Amit Varma]: of looking into Indian affairs.

00:33:58.080 --> 00:34:02.560
[Amit Varma]: And he sort of influences the birth of the IPC in the future.

00:34:02.560 --> 00:34:04.440
[Amit Varma]: Tell me a bit about that and the role he played.

00:34:04.440 --> 00:34:11.060
[Guest]: So Mill was in India house and he was responsible for communication between the East India Company

00:34:11.060 --> 00:34:12.060
[Guest]: and the parliament.

00:34:12.060 --> 00:34:15.760
[Guest]: He was sort of a go between and a very important go between.

00:34:15.760 --> 00:34:20.360
[Guest]: In fact, he wrote, which he himself calls a seminal history of India, but he had never

00:34:20.360 --> 00:34:22.000
[Guest]: been to India.

00:34:22.000 --> 00:34:26.960
[Guest]: So historians have a lot of problem with his history, but he did write a history of India

00:34:26.960 --> 00:34:27.960
[Amit Varma]: as well.

00:34:27.960 --> 00:34:28.960
[Amit Varma]: So he was coming here.

00:34:28.960 --> 00:34:32.000
[Guest]: In fact, you have a long snide remark by Macaulay on his history.

00:34:32.000 --> 00:34:35.480
[Guest]: So and Macaulay and Mill, in fact, didn't get along at all.

00:34:35.480 --> 00:34:39.600
[Guest]: Macaulay very, very famously in parliament when the reforms were going, the charter reforms

00:34:39.600 --> 00:34:45.480
[Guest]: were happening, he made very, very accusatory statements about Mill saying that this person

00:34:45.480 --> 00:34:48.640
[Guest]: does not even know the, he has never been to the country, doesn't know history, but

00:34:48.640 --> 00:34:51.000
[Guest]: he's written a book on history on Indian law.

00:34:51.000 --> 00:34:54.820
[Guest]: And it's very interesting because when they decided to form the first law commission,

00:34:54.820 --> 00:35:00.920
[Guest]: they wanted to send someone there and Macaulay and the East India Company did not get along

00:35:00.920 --> 00:35:04.400
[Guest]: again because he was a member of parliament, a very young one at that.

00:35:04.400 --> 00:35:08.080
[Guest]: He was in his early thirties, was in his early thirties.

00:35:08.080 --> 00:35:12.160
[Guest]: And he used to criticize the East India Company about everything that they were doing in India.

00:35:12.160 --> 00:35:15.000
[Guest]: So, and Mill also did not get along with Macaulay.

00:35:15.000 --> 00:35:21.480
[Guest]: So it was very surprising that when they eventually had the reforms, then the chart, 1830s, the

00:35:21.480 --> 00:35:25.680
[Guest]: charter reforms happened and they decided to have the first law commission and they

00:35:25.680 --> 00:35:30.960
[Guest]: asked for Mill who they should appoint as the first law commissioner, he recommended

00:35:30.960 --> 00:35:33.520
[Guest]: Macaulay, despite having all his differences with him.

00:35:33.520 --> 00:35:35.320
[Guest]: And it was not taken well by the company.

00:35:35.320 --> 00:35:41.440
[Guest]: So Mill actually had to convince the directors to send Macaulay and their relationship improved

00:35:41.440 --> 00:35:43.280
[Guest]: after that, they prepared after that.

00:35:43.280 --> 00:35:47.840
[Guest]: It's very interesting that two people on the opposite ends of an issue work together to

00:35:47.840 --> 00:35:48.840
[Guest]: get us the court.

00:35:48.840 --> 00:35:50.240
[Guest]: Why did he want Macaulay?

00:35:50.240 --> 00:35:54.680
[Guest]: Because he had a lot of belief in Macaulay's intellectual capacity.

00:35:54.680 --> 00:35:56.400
[Guest]: And he respected Macaulay for that.

00:35:56.400 --> 00:36:01.360
[Guest]: Personally, they may have animosity, but he respected Macaulay for his intellectual capacity.

00:36:01.360 --> 00:36:07.080
[Amit Varma]: And what was Macaulay's approach to like 1833, the commission was set up to sort of draft

00:36:07.080 --> 00:36:08.080
[Amit Varma]: the IPC.

00:36:08.080 --> 00:36:12.000
[Amit Varma]: He took around four years to do it and working practically alone, as you point out, without

00:36:12.000 --> 00:36:13.000
[Amit Varma]: any assistant.

00:36:13.000 --> 00:36:16.600
[Amit Varma]: What was his approach given that he's not exactly writing on a blank slate?

00:36:16.600 --> 00:36:20.760
[Amit Varma]: Because India, though it's not India then, but India as it is, then the lands that he's

00:36:20.760 --> 00:36:26.360
[Amit Varma]: making this legal code for is like you pointed out, so diverse, they have so many different

00:36:26.360 --> 00:36:30.240
[Amit Varma]: kinds of customs and traditions and peoples and ways of doing things.

00:36:30.240 --> 00:36:34.520
[Amit Varma]: So what are the sort of unifying principles which he brings to bear on that?

00:36:34.520 --> 00:36:39.120
[Guest]: So like I said, we had regulations then so it was not really a clean slate.

00:36:39.120 --> 00:36:42.880
[Guest]: But he had a major issue with those regulations.

00:36:42.880 --> 00:36:47.800
[Guest]: And in his notes, he mentions that there's not a lot of popular support for a penal code

00:36:47.800 --> 00:36:49.000
[Guest]: in India.

00:36:49.000 --> 00:36:52.440
[Guest]: That is one of the reasons why the code did not come into effect for 30 years after it

00:36:52.440 --> 00:36:53.800
[Guest]: was originally drafted.

00:36:53.800 --> 00:36:57.880
[Guest]: So when he was looking at the law in his notes, he mentions when he was sending it to Auckland

00:36:57.880 --> 00:37:03.440
[Guest]: for his consideration, he mentions that he's studied other indigenous laws, he studied

00:37:03.440 --> 00:37:08.960
[Guest]: these regulations, and he feels that he does not have anything to refer to, to create these

00:37:08.960 --> 00:37:09.960
[Guest]: laws.

00:37:09.960 --> 00:37:12.280
[Guest]: He feels that nothing is reliable.

00:37:12.280 --> 00:37:17.920
[Guest]: So he actually goes back on old English laws and common law in place there.

00:37:17.920 --> 00:37:21.800
[Guest]: And that is why I said that it's not technically a code because this is not something which

00:37:21.800 --> 00:37:22.800
[Guest]: was brought together.

00:37:22.800 --> 00:37:26.080
[Guest]: It's not a product of bringing together of Indian laws, indigenous laws.

00:37:26.080 --> 00:37:28.320
[Guest]: It's a foreign product at the end of the day.

00:37:28.320 --> 00:37:31.680
[Amit Varma]: So typically, a code would be that you take a bunch of existing laws and you make sense

00:37:31.680 --> 00:37:32.680
[Guest]: of them rationalize them.

00:37:32.680 --> 00:37:33.680
[Guest]: Just put it in a box.

00:37:33.680 --> 00:37:34.680
[Guest]: Just put it in a box.

00:37:34.680 --> 00:37:35.680
[Guest]: This is almost sui generis.

00:37:35.680 --> 00:37:36.680
[Guest]: He's having to come up with...

00:37:36.680 --> 00:37:38.800
[Guest]: He had to come up with a lot of things.

00:37:38.800 --> 00:37:39.800
[Guest]: And that too without help.

00:37:39.800 --> 00:37:43.560
[Guest]: Like I said, almost all the members were sick or back in England or just did not do any

00:37:43.560 --> 00:37:44.560
[Amit Varma]: work.

00:37:44.560 --> 00:37:45.560
[Amit Varma]: So what are his guiding principles?

00:37:45.560 --> 00:37:49.440
[Amit Varma]: He of course was an influence, I guess, the whole utilitarian funda is there.

00:37:49.440 --> 00:37:52.120
[Amit Varma]: But what are his guiding principles otherwise?

00:37:52.120 --> 00:37:55.720
[Guest]: His guiding principle mostly was proportionality and certainty.

00:37:55.720 --> 00:37:56.720
[Guest]: He wanted that.

00:37:56.720 --> 00:38:00.120
[Guest]: And he wanted clear categories of offenses to be created.

00:38:00.120 --> 00:38:06.240
[Guest]: If you look at the draft code, it's arranged in a way in which if you're talking about

00:38:06.240 --> 00:38:10.800
[Guest]: laws against the human body, then they all club together like we have in the IPC today.

00:38:10.800 --> 00:38:12.320
[Guest]: It comes from there.

00:38:12.320 --> 00:38:17.240
[Guest]: So he wanted extreme clarity as far as application of penal laws was concerned.

00:38:17.240 --> 00:38:21.800
[Amit Varma]: And you know, you sum it up very nicely where by quoting McCauley when McCauley says about

00:38:21.800 --> 00:38:27.040
