[Guest]: And the punishment is the same for saying something or actually causing an uprising.

00:49:44.960 --> 00:49:47.080
[Amit Varma]: So yes, that equivalence doesn't exist.

00:49:47.080 --> 00:49:51.440
[Amit Varma]: And you know, in one of the things that you keep talking about in your book and demonstrating

00:49:51.440 --> 00:49:56.000
[Amit Varma]: in your book is that you can't just look at laws in isolation, you see them in the political

00:49:56.000 --> 00:49:58.720
[Amit Varma]: context of the time, the social context of the time.

00:49:58.720 --> 00:50:03.280
[Amit Varma]: And so, you know, Macaulay between 33 and 37 works on this code, he gets it out, but

00:50:03.280 --> 00:50:07.360
[Amit Varma]: then it's kind of stuck in the bureaucracy and is being debated back and forth.

00:50:07.360 --> 00:50:11.520
[Amit Varma]: And like you pointed out, Bethune does an alternative version of it and so on.

00:50:11.520 --> 00:50:16.680
[Amit Varma]: But then a strong impetus is given to it by circumstances, which is basically the revolt

00:50:16.680 --> 00:50:17.680
[Amit Varma]: of 1857.

00:50:17.680 --> 00:50:19.680
[Amit Varma]: Can you tell me a little bit about that?

00:50:19.680 --> 00:50:23.040
