[Guest]: to write it again and to make it a better law as such, define it a little more.

00:51:38.660 --> 00:51:47.660
[Guest]: So the penal code was an exercise in having a unified penal provision, unified penal provisions

00:51:47.660 --> 00:51:54.040
[Guest]: in India to control the masses and to avoid another 1857 from happening.

00:51:54.040 --> 00:51:57.040
[Guest]: So that is how the crown wanted to assert itself.

00:51:57.040 --> 00:52:03.120
[Amit Varma]: And it strikes me that there are two sort of simultaneous imperatives here, which is

00:52:03.120 --> 00:52:08.620
[Amit Varma]: driving the British to sort of impose this penal code and one is of course, to protect

00:52:08.620 --> 00:52:10.640
[Amit Varma]: themselves and to control the people.

00:52:10.640 --> 00:52:17.260
[Amit Varma]: But the other also is a transformative one to sort of to bring about social change, which

00:52:17.260 --> 00:52:20.820
[Amit Varma]: is something you know, even Macaulay, for example, is notorious for having spoken about

00:52:20.820 --> 00:52:24.260
[Amit Varma]: the civilizing impulse of empire and so on.

00:52:24.260 --> 00:52:29.380
[Amit Varma]: So does the IPC sort of contain reflect both of these imperatives?

00:52:29.380 --> 00:52:30.380
[Guest]: Yes, it does.

00:52:30.380 --> 00:52:38.980
[Guest]: In fact, I would be amiss to mention that Macaulay as such wasn't your ideal administrator.

00:52:38.980 --> 00:52:43.980
[Guest]: His philosophies that have find origin racist thought.

00:52:43.980 --> 00:52:48.660
[Guest]: He like you mentioned, he wanted to civilize the masses, the education system that he brought

00:52:48.660 --> 00:52:52.400
[Guest]: about in the country that was also to civilize the masses.

00:52:52.400 --> 00:52:55.720
[Guest]: So there was a racist bone in his body.

00:52:55.720 --> 00:53:02.100
[Guest]: But so the law sort of even if you look at like the law of adultery, like women were

00:53:02.100 --> 00:53:05.580
[Guest]: treated as shattered as property, thankfully, that laws gone now.

00:53:05.580 --> 00:53:12.740
[Guest]: So only a man would be punished for adultery, not the woman who participated in that act.

00:53:12.740 --> 00:53:17.060
[Amit Varma]: In fact, the man who slept with the wife of someone else would basically be prosecuted

00:53:17.060 --> 00:53:21.500
[Guest]: for theft because he was taking yes, the property was the wife's was this is a Victorian law.

00:53:21.500 --> 00:53:24.140
[Guest]: We did not have such a concept in India back then.

00:53:24.140 --> 00:53:26.420
[Guest]: So he wanted that concept to be brought in.

00:53:26.420 --> 00:53:29.740
[Guest]: He wanted that was a complete that was foreign to us.

00:53:29.740 --> 00:53:33.820
[Guest]: He wanted that to be brought in because then you elevate or rather denigrate a woman to

00:53:33.820 --> 00:53:37.500
[Guest]: a status of property.

00:53:37.500 --> 00:53:42.600
[Guest]: Similarly like social reform, if you say that they wanted to reform and in fact, the great

00:53:42.600 --> 00:53:46.460
[Guest]: leaders of the day like Tilak also, they did not oppose it in principle.

00:53:46.460 --> 00:53:50.620
[Guest]: He personally did not oppose it in principle, but he thought that it should be left to the

00:53:50.620 --> 00:53:55.620
[Guest]: natives to the Hindus to do it themselves, do a reform, have awareness program like about

00:53:55.620 --> 00:54:00.540
[Guest]: the age of consent bill, where there's this tradition of which was the Garbhdan that on

00:54:00.540 --> 00:54:03.940
[Guest]: the first night itself, the child bride would sleep with the man and it didn't matter he

00:54:03.940 --> 00:54:05.460
[Guest]: was 30 or 40.

00:54:05.460 --> 00:54:07.740
[Guest]: And there was a death which happened because of that.

00:54:07.740 --> 00:54:10.780
[Guest]: Now, people did not react well to these changes.

00:54:10.780 --> 00:54:15.740
[Guest]: And these changes were brought, they tried to impose these changes through legislation,

00:54:15.740 --> 00:54:19.020
[Guest]: which was alien for people back then.

00:54:19.020 --> 00:54:23.060
[Guest]: So there was the like you said, they did try to civilize the masses if I may use their

00:54:23.060 --> 00:54:24.700
[Guest]: language rather than our language.

00:54:24.700 --> 00:54:26.820
[Guest]: They did want to civilize the masses through these laws.

00:54:26.820 --> 00:54:31.220
[Amit Varma]: In fact, it's best used in inverted quotes, because the transformative effect that they

00:54:31.220 --> 00:54:35.740
[Amit Varma]: wanted to have sort of seemed to me to fail in two ways.

00:54:35.740 --> 00:54:40.580
[Amit Varma]: In one, of course, they are imposing Victorian values on India, which you could say are actually

00:54:40.580 --> 00:54:43.420
[Amit Varma]: a step backwards from where we are.

00:54:43.420 --> 00:54:49.260
[Amit Varma]: And two, even when they are trying to bring about positive social change, the point of

00:54:49.260 --> 00:54:55.180
[Amit Varma]: Tilak, and this is a classic conservative criticism, which many others, I mean, Tilak,

00:54:55.180 --> 00:54:59.860
[Amit Varma]: I don't think was a classic conservative, but the criticism itself is very Burkean is

00:54:59.860 --> 00:55:04.420
[Amit Varma]: that you cannot change society in a top down way, you have to change it from within, you

00:55:04.420 --> 00:55:07.420
[Guest]: have to change the culture and just having a law doesn't.

00:55:07.420 --> 00:55:09.300
[Guest]: So in fact, it's very interesting.

00:55:09.300 --> 00:55:15.580
[Guest]: So Tilak did not actually oppose this reform, but what he said was that you should make

00:55:15.580 --> 00:55:22.660
[Guest]: people take a pledge that they will not force their girls into marriage at 10 or they will

00:55:22.660 --> 00:55:27.660
[Guest]: not force their girls to do garbhdan on the first night and none of his fellow reformers

00:55:27.660 --> 00:55:29.180
[Guest]: nobody wanted to do that.

00:55:29.180 --> 00:55:30.180
[Guest]: Nobody wanted to take that pledge.

00:55:30.180 --> 00:55:34.220
[Guest]: He said, no, first you may create awareness, you make people do this voluntarily don't

00:55:34.220 --> 00:55:35.820
[Guest]: impose it on them.

00:55:35.820 --> 00:55:42.460
[Guest]: So Tilak while approaching this from a conservative place, he was not against reform, but he knew

00:55:42.460 --> 00:55:46.060
[Guest]: the reality of the day that people will not accept this.

00:55:46.060 --> 00:55:49.460
[Guest]: If let's say someone like Tilak would have initiated the idea, people would have been

00:55:49.460 --> 00:55:51.060
[Guest]: more welcoming of it.

00:55:51.060 --> 00:55:54.660
[Guest]: But because the idea did not come from Tilak, it came from the British.

00:55:54.660 --> 00:55:59.260
[Guest]: So anyway, resentment had started that was the period when actual resentment against

00:55:59.260 --> 00:56:01.080
[Guest]: the government had started.

00:56:01.080 --> 00:56:05.980
[Guest]: It was where the, I would say the freedom movement had started taking form, not the

00:56:05.980 --> 00:56:09.940
[Guest]: freedom movement, I said with anti British movement had started taking form.

00:56:09.940 --> 00:56:11.540
[Guest]: So they thought there is a foreign influence.

00:56:11.540 --> 00:56:12.980
[Guest]: Why should we listen to foreign influence?

00:56:12.980 --> 00:56:15.860
[Guest]: Why should we listen to these people who not even from here?

00:56:15.860 --> 00:56:18.240
[Guest]: Why should we listen to the white skin people?

00:56:18.240 --> 00:56:22.780
[Guest]: So Tilak was right in a way that it has to come from within.

00:56:22.780 --> 00:56:27.580
[Guest]: But yes, people generally averse to these reforms.

00:56:27.580 --> 00:56:29.320
[Guest]: Even Sati was opposed.

00:56:29.320 --> 00:56:33.060
[Guest]: If you think about it today, I for the life of me can't imagine why it was opposed.

00:56:33.060 --> 00:56:35.340
[Guest]: Like I don't know why it was opposed.

00:56:35.340 --> 00:56:37.700
[Guest]: Yes, customs, religion, everything.

00:56:37.700 --> 00:56:44.000
[Guest]: But to kill someone just because their husband is dead, doesn't sound sound nice to me today.

00:56:44.000 --> 00:56:47.740
[Guest]: But at that time, it was opposed because it was the British who brought it.

00:56:47.740 --> 00:56:54.700
[Guest]: So it was more and more resistance to foreign reforms than reforms themselves.

00:56:54.700 --> 00:57:00.500
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, and I had Jerry Rao on my show last week talking about Indian conservatism.

00:57:00.500 --> 00:57:04.900
[Amit Varma]: And his point about conservatism, I think would be that conservatives aren't necessarily

00:57:04.900 --> 00:57:08.340
[Amit Varma]: opposed to reform, but they are very concerned about the manner of reform that if you try

00:57:08.340 --> 00:57:13.700
[Amit Varma]: to impose it in a top down way or try to do it radically, things can go wrong.

00:57:13.700 --> 00:57:17.420
[Amit Varma]: Of course, my counter argument to that is that for something like Sati, you have to

00:57:17.420 --> 00:57:21.860
[Amit Varma]: be animated by first principles that taking someone's life is wrong, coercion is wrong.

00:57:21.860 --> 00:57:26.260
[Amit Varma]: So you don't then wait for society to change once you have figured out that these are your

00:57:26.260 --> 00:57:27.260
[Amit Varma]: values.

00:57:27.260 --> 00:57:31.540
[Amit Varma]: So people could argue that not everyone shares those values.

00:57:31.540 --> 00:57:36.500
[Amit Varma]: Now, the interesting thing about the IPC when it's accepted, I think first Jan 1862 is when

00:57:36.500 --> 00:57:41.140
[Amit Varma]: it comes into effect, is that at that point in time, that sedition law is not there.

00:57:41.140 --> 00:57:47.020
[Guest]: Yeah, you know, it's whether it's an oversight or whatever, you know, it's it's slipped through

00:57:47.020 --> 00:57:48.020
[Guest]: the cracks, basically.

00:57:48.020 --> 00:57:49.380
[Unknown]: That's what they say.

00:57:49.380 --> 00:57:51.700
[Guest]: We will never know why.

00:57:51.700 --> 00:57:56.260
[Guest]: There's no literature on why it was not in the Indian Penal Code.

00:57:56.260 --> 00:58:02.460
[Guest]: There's no literature, they blame it on carelessness or they blame it on oversight, but we will

00:58:02.460 --> 00:58:05.780
[Guest]: maybe we'll never know why it was not brought in the first place.

00:58:05.780 --> 00:58:09.900
[Amit Varma]: But very soon there is, as you describe in your book, a movement to sort of bring the

00:58:09.900 --> 00:58:10.900
[Amit Varma]: sedition law back.

00:58:10.900 --> 00:58:14.500
[Amit Varma]: And one of the things driving it, which might be a TIL for many people listening to the

00:58:14.500 --> 00:58:18.820
[Amit Varma]: show is a Wahhabi movement, the growing Wahhabi movement in India, which is, you know, and

00:58:18.820 --> 00:58:23.100
[Amit Varma]: this is really before the organized freedom movement in India really takes birth.

00:58:23.100 --> 00:58:27.900
[Amit Varma]: And the Wahhabi movement is the chief sort of circumstance, which makes the British think

00:58:27.900 --> 00:58:32.740
[Amit Varma]: that, okay, we've got a bunch of laws after 1857 to keep the natives in check.

00:58:32.740 --> 00:58:34.420
[Amit Varma]: But we need more, we need the sedition law.

00:58:34.420 --> 00:58:35.420
[Amit Varma]: Tell me a bit.

00:58:35.420 --> 00:58:41.660
[Guest]: So the Wahhabi, the Indian Wahhabism does not find its origin in Saudi Wahhabism.

00:58:41.660 --> 00:58:47.500
[Guest]: Indian Wahhabism finds its origin in in Uttar Pradesh of all places, like Bareilly.

00:58:47.500 --> 00:58:52.460
[Guest]: And so the Wahhabis at the time of the mutiny in 1857, they in fact did not participate

00:58:52.460 --> 00:58:53.460
[Guest]: in it.

00:58:53.460 --> 00:58:54.460
[Guest]: They were not nationalistic.

00:58:54.460 --> 00:58:55.460
[Guest]: They were communal.

00:58:55.460 --> 00:59:00.540
[Guest]: They did not want a India without the British.

00:59:00.540 --> 00:59:02.760
[Guest]: They wanted an Islamic India.

00:59:02.760 --> 00:59:05.140
[Guest]: So they sort of stayed away from the movement.

00:59:05.140 --> 00:59:09.260
[Guest]: So they actually did not play any role in it, maybe a minor role here and there, but

00:59:09.260 --> 00:59:10.700
[Guest]: they did not play any role in it.

00:59:10.700 --> 00:59:16.420
[Guest]: But after that ended and before it happened, they, earlier they fought, they were fighting

00:59:16.420 --> 00:59:20.820
[Guest]: the Sikhs, then the Sikhs were defeated by the British and there's again, they refocused

00:59:20.820 --> 00:59:22.180
[Guest]: on the British.

00:59:22.180 --> 00:59:27.220
[Guest]: They wanted to just drive away outsiders from the country and create a Islamic nation.

00:59:27.220 --> 00:59:32.220
[Guest]: So after 1857, there were a lot of conspiracies from across the country, from the Bengal presence,

00:59:32.220 --> 00:59:34.980
[Guest]: from Dhaka to Punjab.

00:59:34.980 --> 00:59:38.700
[Guest]: And this was discovered over a period of time and there were major trials which happened

00:59:38.700 --> 00:59:44.180
[Guest]: that happened in Ambala, in Patna, and Delhi, and Wahhabi leaders executed, but they just

00:59:44.180 --> 00:59:46.180
[Guest]: refused to die down.

00:59:46.180 --> 00:59:53.140
[Guest]: So they actually felt that they need this against the Wahhabis because they could not

00:59:53.140 --> 00:59:57.500
[Guest]: deal with another uprising that close to the mutiny.

00:59:57.500 --> 01:00:02.500
[Guest]: So that is the most proximate cause for Section 124A being enacted.

01:00:02.500 --> 01:00:07.340
[Amit Varma]: So Section 124A comes back and it's also very interesting that you talk about two preventive

01:00:07.340 --> 01:00:10.780
[Amit Varma]: laws to supplement Section 124A.

01:00:10.780 --> 01:00:16.660
[Amit Varma]: The first you point out is a Dramatic Performances Act of 1876, which is, quote, intended to

01:00:16.660 --> 01:00:23.780
[Amit Varma]: prevent performances of seditious, defamatory or scandalous nature, stop quote.

01:00:23.780 --> 01:00:27.460
[Amit Varma]: And of course, all of that is open to interpretation and anything can be and you point out very

01:00:27.460 --> 01:00:29.820
[Amit Varma]: interestingly in the title of this play could be really modern.

01:00:29.820 --> 01:00:34.560
[Amit Varma]: You talk about this play called Chai Ka Darpan, which was a proximate cause for the enactment

01:00:34.560 --> 01:00:40.780
[Amit Varma]: of the law because Chai Ka Darpan was a play that portrayed owners, quote, portrayed owners

01:00:40.780 --> 01:00:45.620
[Amit Varma]: of tea plantations and promoters of migration to tea growing districts as evil persons who

01:00:45.620 --> 01:00:49.660
[Amit Varma]: exploited migrants both physically and sexually, stop quote.

01:00:49.660 --> 01:00:54.260
[Amit Varma]: And as you point out in one of the witticisms that, pepper your book, if there is one rule

01:00:54.260 --> 01:00:57.780
[Amit Varma]: you don't break, it's that you do not mess with the Englishman's tea.

01:00:57.780 --> 01:01:05.700
[Guest]: So these plantations which were across Assam, Bengal, they sort of fed England, the tea

01:01:05.700 --> 01:01:07.280
[Guest]: went from here.

01:01:07.280 --> 01:01:11.140
[Guest]: But a lot of exploitation was happening on these plantations.

01:01:11.140 --> 01:01:13.880
[Guest]: Migrant labor was being badly exploited.

01:01:13.880 --> 01:01:18.180
[Guest]: Number one, we were subjects and number two, they were even the financial overlords.

01:01:18.180 --> 01:01:23.300
[Guest]: So it was rather a communist movement, if I may say so, that people got together and

01:01:23.300 --> 01:01:28.100
[Guest]: they started writing and writing plays and performing plays where they criticize all

01:01:28.100 --> 01:01:29.280
[Guest]: this.

01:01:29.280 --> 01:01:32.580
[Guest]: So the British government was spurred into action because one play, there were other

01:01:32.580 --> 01:01:35.480
[Guest]: plays also and other poetry and stuff.

01:01:35.480 --> 01:01:37.900
[Amit Varma]: There is a play, Chai Ka Darpan exists?

01:01:37.900 --> 01:01:43.520
[Guest]: So I couldn't locate it myself, but yeah, this play existed and they had to ban it.

01:01:43.520 --> 01:01:45.200
[Amit Varma]: So what I meant was, have you read it?

01:01:45.200 --> 01:01:47.400
[Guest]: No, no, I couldn't find the text of the play.

01:01:47.400 --> 01:01:52.240
[Guest]: I had to glean it from the trials and from the history of the law and the speeches which

01:01:52.240 --> 01:01:55.180
[Guest]: were delivered before that act was brought in.

01:01:55.180 --> 01:01:58.560
[Guest]: So when that happened, that's when these laws came in to supplement the laws that, okay,

01:01:58.560 --> 01:02:02.260
[Guest]: fine, we have a general law, but let's have these laws also separately.

01:02:02.260 --> 01:02:07.560
[Amit Varma]: And the other law, which I also found interesting, the other preventive law was the Vernacular

01:02:07.560 --> 01:02:13.200
[Amit Varma]: Press Act of 1878, which was, quote, enacted to place newspapers published in local languages

01:02:13.200 --> 01:02:17.240
[Amit Varma]: under the control of the government for repressing seditious writings, which are intended to

01:02:17.240 --> 01:02:20.580
[Amit Varma]: produce disaffection towards the government in the mind of natives, stop quote.

01:02:20.580 --> 01:02:24.620
[Amit Varma]: And when I was reading this, it kind of struck me that we don't have that law today.

01:02:24.620 --> 01:02:28.760
[Amit Varma]: But effectively, the same kind of pressures and incentives can still apply.

01:02:28.760 --> 01:02:34.880
[Amit Varma]: You still, for example, no FM radio station will ever dare to talk about politics or broadcast

01:02:34.880 --> 01:02:38.120
[Amit Varma]: actual news because their license could be taken away.

01:02:38.120 --> 01:02:43.340
[Amit Varma]: Or for that matter, you know, different kinds of pressure can be put on all kinds of publications

01:02:43.340 --> 01:02:49.220
[Amit Varma]: because a lot of publications depend on government advertising for their revenues.

01:02:49.220 --> 01:02:53.160
[Amit Varma]: So these pools and pressures still exist, except that there is really no need of a law

01:02:53.160 --> 01:02:54.840
[Guest]: to sort of make it happen.

01:02:54.840 --> 01:02:57.920
[Guest]: It can be controlled economically rather than anything else.

01:02:57.920 --> 01:03:03.480
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, let's talk about the first sedition case now and which of 1891.

01:03:03.480 --> 01:03:09.400
[Amit Varma]: And before we talk about the first sedition case, and it's very interesting how what dovetails

01:03:09.400 --> 01:03:15.460
[Amit Varma]: into this is one of their, you know, the British again trying to bring about social change

01:03:15.460 --> 01:03:16.460
[Amit Varma]: in India.

01:03:16.460 --> 01:03:22.240
[Amit Varma]: And there is obviously you point out that girls are being married as young as 10 years

01:03:22.240 --> 01:03:26.440
[Amit Varma]: old and, you know, expected to conceive very soon.

01:03:26.440 --> 01:03:31.840
[Amit Varma]: And you talk about this child, right, called full money, who was 10 years old in 1889,

01:03:31.840 --> 01:03:37.640
[Amit Varma]: married off to a man named Hari Mohan Mehti, who was over 30 years of age, and he has sex

01:03:37.640 --> 01:03:40.120
[Amit Varma]: with her and she dies that night itself.

01:03:40.120 --> 01:03:42.860
[Amit Varma]: He's charged for her rape and murder.

01:03:42.860 --> 01:03:46.080
[Amit Varma]: And that leads to the coinage of the term Hari Mehtism, which I must confess, I haven't

01:03:46.080 --> 01:03:51.400
[Amit Varma]: heard till I read your book, Hari Mehtism for the court practice of consummation of

01:03:51.400 --> 01:03:54.160
[Amit Varma]: marriage with child rights, stop quote.

01:03:54.160 --> 01:03:58.920
[Amit Varma]: And he's acquitted because the law against rape does not apply to the marital rape of

01:03:58.920 --> 01:04:01.240
[Amit Varma]: a girl of 10 years of age.

01:04:01.240 --> 01:04:06.640
[Amit Varma]: And at this point, the British government enacts the age of consent act of 18 March

01:04:06.640 --> 01:04:11.340
[Amit Varma]: 1891, which raises the age of consent from 10 to 12.

01:04:11.340 --> 01:04:13.500
[Guest]: So that was a huge leap of two years.

01:04:13.500 --> 01:04:15.160
[Amit Varma]: And everybody goes nuts.

01:04:15.160 --> 01:04:17.360
[Amit Varma]: Tell me a bit about that.

01:04:17.360 --> 01:04:23.720
[Guest]: So again, like I said, reforms for being resisted, and the Bengali intelligentsia, which is a

01:04:23.720 --> 01:04:31.800
[Guest]: bongo bashi that took up issues with it and wrote severe editorials against this reform,

01:04:31.800 --> 01:04:35.960
[Guest]: saying that the British come in and they're touching our Hindu cults terms and traditions,

01:04:35.960 --> 01:04:38.600
[Guest]: they're destroying everything.

01:04:38.600 --> 01:04:42.120
[Guest]: And they say, if these if this keeps happening, we'll have to throw them out.

01:04:42.120 --> 01:04:44.120
[Guest]: I'm just, I'm paraphrasing everything.

01:04:44.120 --> 01:04:49.280
[Amit Varma]: I'll read that bit out where a translated extract of the first offending article which

01:04:49.280 --> 01:04:53.840
[Amit Varma]: was cited in the case goes, quote, the English ruler is our Lord and Master and can interfere

01:04:53.840 --> 01:04:57.880
[Amit Varma]: with our religion and usages by brute force and European civilization.

01:04:57.880 --> 01:05:02.740
[Amit Varma]: The Hindu is powerless to resist, but he is superior to your nation and good morals in

01:05:02.740 --> 01:05:07.260
[Amit Varma]: gentle conduct and in good education, Hindu civilization and the Hindu religion are in

01:05:07.260 --> 01:05:08.900
[Amit Varma]: danger of being destroyed.

01:05:08.900 --> 01:05:11.800
[Amit Varma]: The Englishman stands revealed in his true colors.

01:05:11.800 --> 01:05:17.320
[Amit Varma]: He has a rifle and bayonet and slanders the Hindu from the might of the gun.

01:05:17.320 --> 01:05:19.080
[Amit Varma]: How are we to conciliate him?

01:05:19.080 --> 01:05:20.080
[Amit Varma]: Stop quote.

01:05:20.080 --> 01:05:22.880
[Amit Varma]: And when I read this, I thought, ki Englishman ke jaga mein elites dal do.

01:05:22.880 --> 01:05:23.880
[Unknown]: Exactly.

01:05:23.880 --> 01:05:24.880
[Unknown]: And it still applies.

01:05:24.880 --> 01:05:25.880
[Unknown]: This seems very, very familiar.

01:05:25.880 --> 01:05:26.880
[Unknown]: Doesn't it sound familiar?

01:05:26.880 --> 01:05:31.160
[Unknown]: Yeah, you go on social media, doesn't it sound familiar today that this is exact same thing

01:05:31.160 --> 01:05:34.080
[Unknown]: we are seeing again, the Hindu majority is victim.

01:05:34.080 --> 01:05:35.320
[Unknown]: Hindu khatre mein hai.

01:05:35.320 --> 01:05:38.800
[Amit Varma]: At that time, you could say, they were sort of the victim.

01:05:38.800 --> 01:05:43.240
[Amit Varma]: So anyway, so this guy comes up with this thing that how dare you raise the age to 12,

01:05:43.240 --> 01:05:46.520
[Unknown]: you know, what are 11 year old girls to do?

01:05:46.520 --> 01:05:51.120
[Guest]: And I know, but but but the age for marriage were not raised.

01:05:51.120 --> 01:05:53.340
[Guest]: Only the age for intercourse was raised.

01:05:53.340 --> 01:05:56.220
[Guest]: So you could still have a 10 year old child bride.

01:05:56.220 --> 01:06:01.720
[Guest]: But if you have sex with her before she turned 12, that was marital rape, which seems very

01:06:01.720 --> 01:06:06.200
[Amit Varma]: bizarrely legalistic, because there's no actual way of whoever is implementing the law to

01:06:06.200 --> 01:06:07.200
[Guest]: enforce it.

01:06:07.200 --> 01:06:08.200
[Guest]: Yes.

01:06:08.200 --> 01:06:11.880
[Amit Varma]: So they maybe they wanted to appear to be doing some good virtue signaling.

01:06:11.880 --> 01:06:12.880
[Amit Varma]: Yeah.

01:06:12.880 --> 01:06:17.760
[Guest]: It's very interesting today that even today, there's a debate on marital rape happening.

01:06:17.760 --> 01:06:21.520
[Guest]: That the petition spending in the Supreme Court and the High Court where they want marital

01:06:21.520 --> 01:06:22.520
[Guest]: rape to be criminalized.

01:06:22.520 --> 01:06:26.720
[Guest]: So in fact, British did criminalize marital rape for 10 and 11 year old girl child.

01:06:26.720 --> 01:06:30.680
[Amit Varma]: So I guess what you could say is progress is basically the age of marital rape rising.

01:06:30.680 --> 01:06:31.680
[Amit Varma]: Absolutely.

01:06:31.680 --> 01:06:34.920
[Amit Varma]: Jesus, I don't even know what to say.

01:06:34.920 --> 01:06:39.400
[Amit Varma]: Let's talk a bit about this sort of first case where the proprietor, editor, manager

01:06:39.400 --> 01:06:44.680
[Amit Varma]: and printer of Bongo Bashi are all charged in a case known as Queen Empress versus Jogendra

01:06:44.680 --> 01:06:48.920
[Amit Varma]: Chandra Bose and others.

01:06:48.920 --> 01:06:49.920
[Amit Varma]: And others.

01:06:49.920 --> 01:06:50.920
[Guest]: Okay, it's written.

01:06:50.920 --> 01:06:51.920
[Guest]: O.R.S is others.

01:06:51.920 --> 01:06:54.040
[Amit Varma]: What do I know about legal language?

01:06:54.040 --> 01:06:58.040
[Amit Varma]: And one of the defenses, of course, is that hey, you know, we didn't kind of write it.

01:06:58.040 --> 01:07:00.840
[Amit Varma]: I mean, the writer is anonymous, and he's not here.

01:07:00.840 --> 01:07:02.800
[Amit Varma]: So don't blame us and that's kind of thrown out.

01:07:02.800 --> 01:07:08.880
[Amit Varma]: Now the debates around the sedition law, especially the terminology, especially the word disaffection,

01:07:08.880 --> 01:07:11.720
[Guest]: kind of start from this case where Justice Petheram.

01:07:11.720 --> 01:07:12.720
[Guest]: Yeah, Justice Petheram.

01:07:12.720 --> 01:07:16.800
[Amit Varma]: When I read this, I couldn't figure out if he's an Englishman.

01:07:16.800 --> 01:07:18.560
[Unknown]: Englishman, definitely Englishman.

01:07:18.560 --> 01:07:22.240
[Amit Varma]: So not Petheram, but Justice Petheram.

01:07:22.240 --> 01:07:26.320
[Amit Varma]: And so tell me a bit about the debate around this case and kind of what happens.

01:07:26.320 --> 01:07:32.520
[Guest]: So what they did was that they wanted to interpret what disaffection actually means.

01:07:32.520 --> 01:07:38.960
[Guest]: So what he said, it doesn't know what the presence of the letters DIS between affection

01:07:38.960 --> 01:07:41.640
[Guest]: means it has to be the opposite of affection.

01:07:41.640 --> 01:07:44.160
[Guest]: So the opposite of affection is hatred.

01:07:44.160 --> 01:07:47.880
[Guest]: So it doesn't matter if it's a legitimate criticism.

01:07:47.880 --> 01:07:54.680
[Guest]: If they if they if they if he asked the jury to decide whether they felt that was this

01:07:54.680 --> 01:07:58.480
[Guest]: intended to create hatred against the government or not.

01:07:58.480 --> 01:08:02.800
[Guest]: Doesn't matter no violence ensued, doesn't matter that it was a legitimate criticism.

01:08:02.800 --> 01:08:06.160
[Guest]: I say legitimate because of what people felt that back then.

01:08:06.160 --> 01:08:12.720
[Guest]: So he made a very, very literal interpretation of the term disaffection and said that hatred,

01:08:12.720 --> 01:08:17.520
[Amit Varma]: anything to incite hatred against the government would lead to the offense of sedition.

01:08:17.520 --> 01:08:22.760
[Amit Varma]: And the sort of counter interpretation of this is that, you know, you don't that the

01:08:22.760 --> 01:08:26.160
[Amit Varma]: word disaffection in a legal sense has evolved to mean something else.

01:08:26.160 --> 01:08:30.800
[Amit Varma]: And the way the sedition law has also been interpreted is that merely criticizing the

01:08:30.800 --> 01:08:33.800
[Amit Varma]: government or inspiring hatred against it isn't enough.

01:08:33.800 --> 01:08:38.680
[Amit Varma]: You also need to incite people to specific acts of violence against it only then is it

01:08:38.680 --> 01:08:39.680
[Guest]: sedition.

01:08:39.680 --> 01:08:42.800
[Guest]: So that that actually happened later that happened in the 1960s.

01:08:42.800 --> 01:08:47.400
[Guest]: Prior to that, there was no such interpretation built into the law.

01:08:47.400 --> 01:08:50.720
[Guest]: It is actually the Supreme Court which read down the law to include this, that actual

01:08:50.720 --> 01:08:52.920
[Guest]: incitement of hatred has to happen.

01:08:52.920 --> 01:08:58.240
[Guest]: But before that, mere criticism which which would cause disloyalty or hatred against the

01:08:58.240 --> 01:09:00.880
[Guest]: government was enough to be punished for sedition.

01:09:00.880 --> 01:09:04.560
[Amit Varma]: But this is Peter M's interpretation of disaffection that there were other interpretations which

01:09:04.560 --> 01:09:05.560
[Guest]: came up.

01:09:05.560 --> 01:09:09.480
[Guest]: The interpretation was Morris Goyer which happened a lot later in the 1940s.

01:09:09.480 --> 01:09:15.000
[Guest]: And he sort of said what Kedarnath judgment said eventually, that unless there's incitement

01:09:15.000 --> 01:09:17.840
[Guest]: to violence, you can't punish a person for sedition.

01:09:17.840 --> 01:09:20.320
[Guest]: But it was quickly set aside with the Privy Council in another case.

01:09:20.320 --> 01:09:22.280
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, we'll come to that.

01:09:22.280 --> 01:09:24.000
[Amit Varma]: Let's move on to the Tilak case.

01:09:24.000 --> 01:09:27.840
[Amit Varma]: You know, Tilak was, you know, a member of the governor's legislative council.

01:09:27.840 --> 01:09:30.840
[Amit Varma]: And he was a fairly big guy within local circles at the time.

01:09:30.840 --> 01:09:35.080
[Amit Varma]: And he had this newspaper called Kesri.

01:09:35.080 --> 01:09:40.380
[Amit Varma]: And the first case against him really comes because he seems to justify violence, especially

01:09:40.380 --> 01:09:47.400
[Amit Varma]: in the context of Shivaji, where, you know, he essentially argues that Shivaji was justified

01:09:47.400 --> 01:09:51.240
[Amit Varma]: in killing Afzal Khan in the way that he did that it was an act of self defense.

01:09:51.240 --> 01:09:57.960
[Amit Varma]: And therefore, to use that as an analogy against the empire, that there are modern circumstances,

01:09:57.960 --> 01:10:01.320
[Amit Varma]: contemporary circumstances, in which case such violence may be justified.

01:10:01.320 --> 01:10:03.440
[Amit Varma]: And obviously, he was hold up for sedition.

01:10:03.440 --> 01:10:07.080
[Amit Varma]: What are the sort of arguments going back and forth?

01:10:07.080 --> 01:10:11.480
[Guest]: So what had actually happened was that there was a plague in Pune, prior to all that.

01:10:11.480 --> 01:10:15.920
[Guest]: And a lot of people died and they were really resisting the government's effort to rescue

01:10:15.920 --> 01:10:19.040
[Guest]: victims or to quarantine people.

01:10:19.040 --> 01:10:22.360
[Guest]: So there was this plague commissioner Rand.

01:10:22.360 --> 01:10:26.320
[Guest]: And so people really detested him.

01:10:26.320 --> 01:10:32.040
[Guest]: In fact, Tilak himself had a huge hand to play in getting people to accept government

01:10:32.040 --> 01:10:35.920
[Guest]: help getting them into hospitals, leave their homes because they were very afraid of British

01:10:35.920 --> 01:10:36.920
[Amit Varma]: help.

01:10:36.920 --> 01:10:39.160
[Amit Varma]: And what these Britishers were basically doing is they were coming home and if they found

01:10:39.160 --> 01:10:42.120
[Amit Varma]: a victim, just send them off to the hospital.

01:10:42.120 --> 01:10:44.360
[Guest]: And burn all their possessions.

01:10:44.360 --> 01:10:48.640
[Amit Varma]: So you're having people whose homes are being invaded, their relatives being sent away to

01:10:48.640 --> 01:10:51.560
[Amit Varma]: a hospital, and their things being burnt.

01:10:51.560 --> 01:10:54.720
[Amit Varma]: And sometimes if there's no one else at home, the houses just left like that.

01:10:54.720 --> 01:10:55.720
[Guest]: Yes.

01:10:55.720 --> 01:11:00.720
[Guest]: So basically, that's why the natives of Pune, they felt that this was an act of aggression

01:11:00.720 --> 01:11:02.280
[Guest]: against the local population.

01:11:02.280 --> 01:11:04.320
[Guest]: In fact, they were trying to help them.

01:11:04.320 --> 01:11:10.960
[Guest]: And soon after that, the Shivaji festival was, I would say it was reborn in the years

01:11:10.960 --> 01:11:12.320
[Guest]: around that time.

01:11:12.320 --> 01:11:18.360
[Guest]: And when he delivered the speech, sometime after that, days after that, Rand was assassinated

01:11:18.360 --> 01:11:21.440
[Guest]: because of this plague relief work.

01:11:21.440 --> 01:11:28.120
[Guest]: Now the British then need an excuse to catch the luck for something.

01:11:28.120 --> 01:11:31.700
[Guest]: Even though he was a member of the legislative council, and he was a very important man,

01:11:31.700 --> 01:11:33.360
[Guest]: but they still detested him.

01:11:33.360 --> 01:11:35.400
[Guest]: He was seen as a power center, separate power centers.

01:11:35.400 --> 01:11:37.640
[Guest]: Again, it was very political.

01:11:37.640 --> 01:11:43.440
[Guest]: And the newspapers, the Anglo-Indian newspapers like the Times of India, and the English language

01:11:43.440 --> 01:11:46.920
[Guest]: newspapers were really against these vernacular papers or Indians running English papers like

01:11:46.920 --> 01:11:51.960
[Guest]: the Maratha was actually an English paper and Kesari was the vernacular paper, Marathi

01:11:51.960 --> 01:11:52.960
[Guest]: paper.

01:11:52.960 --> 01:11:56.440
[Guest]: So when this was reported, when these speeches which he delivered and other people delivered

01:11:56.440 --> 01:12:02.800
[Guest]: in those, in Raikad, they tried to join it.

01:12:02.800 --> 01:12:06.920
[Guest]: They have tried to create a proximity with assassination.

01:12:06.920 --> 01:12:11.160
[Guest]: And when they raided him, they found literature, which he still, he claimed that it was not

01:12:11.160 --> 01:12:12.160
[Guest]: his.

01:12:12.160 --> 01:12:18.000
[Guest]: So they found literature about subversive activities.

01:12:18.000 --> 01:12:22.600
[Guest]: So they actually arrested him at that point of time to send a message to the vernacular

01:12:22.600 --> 01:12:25.800
[Guest]: press and to the people around at that point of time.

01:12:25.800 --> 01:12:28.320
[Guest]: And his defense was that this is not sedition.

01:12:28.320 --> 01:12:32.040
[Guest]: His defense was there's nothing in his speeches where he tries to incite hatred against the

01:12:32.040 --> 01:12:33.580
[Guest]: government.

01:12:33.580 --> 01:12:38.500
[Guest]: So he actually tried to raise a defense within the law.

01:12:38.500 --> 01:12:39.500
[Guest]: He tried to defend himself.

01:12:39.500 --> 01:12:40.500
[Guest]: He did not have legal help.

01:12:40.500 --> 01:12:42.440
[Guest]: He did everything himself.

01:12:42.440 --> 01:12:47.920
[Guest]: So his defense was that he did not say or utter anything which could incite hatred against

01:12:47.920 --> 01:12:48.920
[Guest]: the government.

01:12:48.920 --> 01:12:51.200
[Guest]: In fact, looked at my other work that I've done.

01:12:51.200 --> 01:12:54.120
[Guest]: I'm actually supporting the government and the government's efforts.

01:12:54.120 --> 01:12:55.480
[Amit Varma]: That was his defense.

01:12:55.480 --> 01:12:59.400
[Amit Varma]: And at one point he had when he couldn't find anyone to defend him, Rabindranath Tagore

01:12:59.400 --> 01:13:03.280
[Amit Varma]: got him these two notes from Calcutta.

01:13:03.280 --> 01:13:07.160
[Amit Varma]: And you know, one of those lawyers say something really interesting in his defense of Tilak,

01:13:07.160 --> 01:13:11.840
[Amit Varma]: which, you know, leads me to my sort of next question, which is a regression, which is

01:13:11.840 --> 01:13:16.400
[Amit Varma]: quote, if the government seriously believed Tilak guilty of the abetment of murder, it

01:13:16.400 --> 01:13:18.840
[Amit Varma]: ought to have openly accused him of it.

01:13:18.840 --> 01:13:24.080
[Amit Varma]: The very fact that he has not been so charged, but prosecuted under 124A, shows the weakness

01:13:24.080 --> 01:13:29.220
[Amit Varma]: of the government's case, stop quote, at which point it makes me wonder that if the issue

01:13:29.220 --> 01:13:33.720
[Amit Varma]: of sedition is the violence and the damage to property and all of those things, you already

01:13:33.720 --> 01:13:35.560
[Amit Varma]: have laws against all of those things.

01:13:35.560 --> 01:13:36.560
[Amit Varma]: Absolutely.

01:13:36.560 --> 01:13:38.840
[Guest]: Why would you then need a sedition law at all?

01:13:38.840 --> 01:13:40.200
[Guest]: It's a political tool.

01:13:40.200 --> 01:13:43.520
[Guest]: It's not a law to punish a person for, for an act as such.

01:13:43.520 --> 01:13:48.900
[Guest]: It is a law to punish a person for his thought, for his ideology.

01:13:48.900 --> 01:13:51.360
[Guest]: So that was what happened with Tilak as well.

01:13:51.360 --> 01:13:54.640
[Amit Varma]: And to what extent since it's a political tool, as you say, to what extent is it used

01:13:54.640 --> 01:14:02.440
[Amit Varma]: as a chilling effect, whereby, you know, prosecuting Tilak under the sedition law, the proximate

01:14:02.440 --> 01:14:06.120
[Amit Varma]: purpose is that okay, he has done something you disapprove of and you want to punish him

01:14:06.120 --> 01:14:07.120
[Amit Varma]: for it.

01:14:07.120 --> 01:14:11.000
[Amit Varma]: But the larger purpose is that everyone else shuts up because they don't want it to happen

01:14:11.000 --> 01:14:12.000
[Guest]: to them.

01:14:12.000 --> 01:14:13.000
[Guest]: Absolutely.

01:14:13.000 --> 01:14:15.480
[Guest]: Because at the same time, there was some other trials also, which had a larger effect of

01:14:15.480 --> 01:14:16.960
[Guest]: the vernacular press being suppressed.

01:14:16.960 --> 01:14:18.840
[Amit Varma]: So that was a larger issue.

01:14:18.840 --> 01:14:23.000
[Amit Varma]: So you know, one of the things that you know, as we've seen earlier in the narrative, that

01:14:23.000 --> 01:14:28.360
[Amit Varma]: McCauley's code was basically languishing until 1857 creates a political imperative

01:14:28.360 --> 01:14:30.560
[Amit Varma]: and something has to be done.

01:14:30.560 --> 01:14:31.800
[Amit Varma]: And it comes into being.

01:14:31.800 --> 01:14:37.320
[Amit Varma]: And here again, I think a lot of us forget the environment of the early 1900s, early

01:14:37.320 --> 01:14:42.840
[Amit Varma]: 20th century, when, you know, contrary to the peaceful Satyagraha based movements, which

01:14:42.840 --> 01:14:47.240
[Amit Varma]: would, which we now remember from the 20s and 30s and 40s, there was actually a lot

01:14:47.240 --> 01:14:50.480
[Amit Varma]: of violence in the early years of the 20th century, which worried the British.

01:14:50.480 --> 01:14:51.480
[Unknown]: A lot of revolutionary crime.

01:14:51.480 --> 01:14:52.480
[Unknown]: Yes.

01:14:52.480 --> 01:14:56.560
[Amit Varma]: Tell me a little bit about that and how that shaped the government's approach to, you know,

01:14:56.560 --> 01:15:01.760
[Amit Varma]: the sedition law itself and other laws like prevention of seditious meetings act in 19th

01:15:01.760 --> 01:15:02.760
[Amit Varma]: century.

01:15:02.760 --> 01:15:03.760
[Guest]: In 1907, that you talk about.

01:15:03.760 --> 01:15:09.600
[Guest]: So this phenomenon, which I talk about revolutionary crime, it was it originated in Bengal, subsequent

01:15:09.600 --> 01:15:10.600
[Guest]: to the partition of Bengal.

01:15:10.600 --> 01:15:13.240
[Guest]: There was a lot of resentment against the partition.

01:15:13.240 --> 01:15:16.040
[Guest]: They thought they were driving a population against each other.

01:15:16.040 --> 01:15:19.720
[Guest]: In fact, the Nawab of Dhaka initially was against the idea, but subsequently got around

01:15:19.720 --> 01:15:22.920
[Guest]: to it because the British promised him power over that region.

01:15:22.920 --> 01:15:27.240
[Guest]: So it's a, it originated there, but the influence was largely Russian.

01:15:27.240 --> 01:15:34.480
[Guest]: There was a Russian revolution where they discovered the power of a bomb and that spread

01:15:34.480 --> 01:15:37.160
[Guest]: to India, to Bengal and to Punjab.

01:15:37.160 --> 01:15:39.200
[Guest]: And they started creating this age of the bomb.

01:15:39.200 --> 01:15:45.400
[Guest]: They started throwing bombs, crudely made bombs, but they were trying to get hurt.

01:15:45.400 --> 01:15:50.360
[Guest]: Then secret societies formed all over Bengal and what is East Bengal and West Bengal, all

01:15:50.360 --> 01:15:53.760
[Guest]: over East and West Bengal, which were called Anusilan Samitis.

01:15:53.760 --> 01:15:57.640
[Guest]: What these Samitis would do is they would train youngsters as people, children as young

01:15:57.640 --> 01:16:04.920
[Guest]: as 15, 16, 18 to just do violent acts, violent acts of revolution against the government,

01:16:04.920 --> 01:16:07.960
[Guest]: send a message across to the government that we are not going to sit silent.

01:16:07.960 --> 01:16:10.320
[Guest]: So this age as such was a very, very violent age.

01:16:10.320 --> 01:16:12.560
[Guest]: It was more than anything political.

01:16:12.560 --> 01:16:13.900
[Guest]: It was resentment.

01:16:13.900 --> 01:16:18.120
[Guest]: It was actually hated against the government because of the partition.

01:16:18.120 --> 01:16:23.800
[Guest]: And they just discovered these bomb making techniques and literature, which came from

01:16:23.800 --> 01:16:24.800
[Amit Varma]: Russia.

01:16:24.800 --> 01:16:25.800
[Amit Varma]: So it really helped them.

01:16:25.800 --> 01:16:28.200
[Amit Varma]: And it's interesting that, you know, if one looks at the freedom movement, there's obviously

01:16:28.200 --> 01:16:31.840
[Amit Varma]: the division between the moderates and the extremists and the moderates like, you know,

01:16:31.840 --> 01:16:35.800
[Amit Varma]: Gokhale Ranade Agarkar and so on, believe in the power of petitioning and they want

01:16:35.800 --> 01:16:40.000
[Unknown]: to sort of work with the power of cooperation and all that.

01:16:40.000 --> 01:16:46.120
[Amit Varma]: And the so called extremists like, you know, Tilak and Annie Besant and Banerjee are figuring

01:16:46.120 --> 01:16:49.400
[Amit Varma]: out that that has its limits.

01:16:49.400 --> 01:16:54.600
[Amit Varma]: So B. R. Nanda in a great biography of Gokhale once said something to the effect of the moderates

01:16:54.600 --> 01:16:58.600
[Amit Varma]: are extreme in their moderation and the extremists are moderate in their extremism.

01:16:58.600 --> 01:17:00.160
[Amit Varma]: So they weren't all that far apart.

01:17:00.160 --> 01:17:05.440
[Amit Varma]: But the thing is, this seems to me about that point in time where people are realizing the

01:17:05.440 --> 01:17:09.000
[Amit Varma]: futility of trying to negotiate with the colonial government.

01:17:09.000 --> 01:17:12.120
[Amit Varma]: Though Gandhi is trying that in South Africa, and he comes back and he continues trying

01:17:12.120 --> 01:17:18.000
[Amit Varma]: that till, you know, the second half of the second decade.

01:17:18.000 --> 01:17:21.720
[Amit Varma]: But and now all these violent impulses are beginning to play out.

01:17:21.720 --> 01:17:24.160
[Amit Varma]: There's Aurobindo Ghosh and his brother.

01:17:24.160 --> 01:17:25.480
[Amit Varma]: There's what is happening in London.

01:17:25.480 --> 01:17:29.320
[Amit Varma]: I mean, there are two recent biographies on Savarkar which talk about India house and

01:17:29.320 --> 01:17:30.480
[Amit Varma]: the stuff that is happening there.

01:17:30.480 --> 01:17:34.880
[Amit Varma]: In fact, his brother Ganesh Savarkar was, as you point out in your book, convicted for

01:17:34.880 --> 01:17:35.880
[Guest]: writing poems.

01:17:35.880 --> 01:17:36.880
[Guest]: Yes.

01:17:36.880 --> 01:17:37.880
[Guest]: This was in Nashik.

01:17:37.880 --> 01:17:43.680
[Amit Varma]: He was convicted for writing poems which are considered subversive and seditious.

01:17:43.680 --> 01:17:46.600
[Amit Varma]: And Savarkar is, Vinayak Savarkar is very pissed off at this.

01:17:46.600 --> 01:17:50.440
[Amit Varma]: He's in London at the time and he gets in, allegedly gets an associate of his mother-in-law

01:17:50.440 --> 01:17:53.480
[Amit Varma]: Dhingra to go and assassinate a British guy.

01:17:53.480 --> 01:17:55.400
[Amit Varma]: And assassinate the wrong guy.

01:17:55.400 --> 01:17:59.640
[Amit Varma]: Assassinates the wrong guy and that sets off a chain of events which leads to Savarkar

01:17:59.640 --> 01:18:04.800
[Amit Varma]: being sent to Kalapani for 10 years where he is completely radicalized and then he comes

01:18:04.800 --> 01:18:06.080
[Amit Varma]: out and writes Hindutva.

01:18:06.080 --> 01:18:08.640
[Amit Varma]: So what would have happened if he wasn't arrested?

01:18:08.640 --> 01:18:09.640
[Amit Varma]: Yes.

01:18:09.640 --> 01:18:13.120
[Amit Varma]: Is this so much sort of, I mean, the counterfactuals are so incredibly fascinating.

01:18:13.120 --> 01:18:15.120
[Amit Varma]: You should one day write a book of fiction about it.

01:18:15.120 --> 01:18:18.360
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, I know what you're talking about.

01:18:18.360 --> 01:18:19.360
[Amit Varma]: Wink.

01:18:19.360 --> 01:18:20.360
[Amit Varma]: Yeah.

01:18:20.360 --> 01:18:21.360
[Amit Varma]: Wink.

01:18:21.360 --> 01:18:22.760
[Amit Varma]: So, so all of this is happening.

01:18:22.760 --> 01:18:28.740
[Amit Varma]: And at this point, sort of, you know, there are other laws coming up, like there's a prevention

01:18:28.740 --> 01:18:32.200
[Amit Varma]: of seditious meeting acts coming up.

01:18:32.200 --> 01:18:37.240
[Amit Varma]: And Tilak himself is convicted again in a second trial because he praises the making

01:18:37.240 --> 01:18:38.240
[Amit Varma]: of bombs.

01:18:38.240 --> 01:18:39.240
[Amit Varma]: Yes.

01:18:39.240 --> 01:18:41.280
[Amit Varma]: And the raiders home and they apparently find bomb making manuals.

01:18:41.280 --> 01:18:42.280
[Guest]: Is that true?

01:18:42.280 --> 01:18:43.280
[Guest]: He really had bomb making manuals.

01:18:43.280 --> 01:18:45.080
[Guest]: So, it was not really bomb making manuals.

01:18:45.080 --> 01:18:50.680
[Guest]: It didn't teach people how to make bombs, but it related to bombs.

01:18:50.680 --> 01:18:54.760
[Guest]: Like it mentions certain kinds of explosives and stuff like that.

01:18:54.760 --> 01:18:58.080
[Guest]: And when his house was raided, he was not even there.

01:18:58.080 --> 01:18:59.080
[Guest]: He was in Bombay.

01:18:59.080 --> 01:19:00.080
[Amit Varma]: So it could have been planted.

01:19:00.080 --> 01:19:01.080
[Unknown]: It could have been anything.

01:19:01.080 --> 01:19:02.080
[Guest]: We will never know.

01:19:02.080 --> 01:19:03.080
[Guest]: It was not his.

01:19:03.080 --> 01:19:05.000
[Guest]: And he says, even if I have it, how does it matter?

01:19:05.000 --> 01:19:06.760
[Guest]: I have not acted upon it.

01:19:06.760 --> 01:19:08.600
[Guest]: Have you known me to make bombs?

01:19:08.600 --> 01:19:09.600
[Guest]: Exactly.

01:19:09.600 --> 01:19:12.400
[Guest]: So that was that was completely orchestrated again.

01:19:12.400 --> 01:19:16.840
[Guest]: He was, they waited for him to turn up in Bombay before they could arrest him.

01:19:16.840 --> 01:19:17.840
[Guest]: They don't want him tried in Pune.

01:19:17.840 --> 01:19:20.240
[Guest]: They wanted to try and get him tried in Bombay.

01:19:20.240 --> 01:19:23.840
[Guest]: In fact, he turned up there because a buddy of his was to help a buddy of his with a seditious

01:19:23.840 --> 01:19:24.840
[Guest]: case of his own.

01:19:24.840 --> 01:19:25.840
[Guest]: Kaal.

01:19:25.840 --> 01:19:26.840
[Guest]: That was the Kaal trial.

01:19:26.840 --> 01:19:30.920
[Guest]: Paranjpe was being tried for sedition and he had turned up to create his defense.

01:19:30.920 --> 01:19:35.880
[Guest]: In fact, very interesting that Damodar Savarkar also was in Bombay at the same time.

01:19:35.880 --> 01:19:40.560
[Guest]: And when they were agitating against, he was arrested outside the police station then and

01:19:40.560 --> 01:19:44.040
[Guest]: he was arrested and convicted for not for sedition or something else.

01:19:44.040 --> 01:19:45.480
[Guest]: And he gets out and then goes back.

01:19:45.480 --> 01:19:48.480
[Guest]: So it's again a very interesting core connected story.

01:19:48.480 --> 01:19:50.500
[Guest]: All these are connected with each other.

01:19:50.500 --> 01:19:54.200
[Guest]: So yes, it was again a political exercise.

01:19:54.200 --> 01:19:59.560
[Guest]: And again, what he did was that he again defended himself within the confines of the law.

01:19:59.560 --> 01:20:02.360
[Guest]: He again had to foot his own legal defense.

01:20:02.360 --> 01:20:03.760
[Guest]: He had to do everything himself.

01:20:03.760 --> 01:20:10.280
[Guest]: He stood up and spoke in court for more than 24 hours, like combined total of 24, 27 hours.

01:20:10.280 --> 01:20:11.280
[Amit Varma]: Practically a filibuster speech.

01:20:11.280 --> 01:20:12.280
[Guest]: Yes, a filibuster speech.

01:20:12.280 --> 01:20:17.920
[Amit Varma]: His speech started on 15 July and concluded on 22nd July.

01:20:17.920 --> 01:20:19.760
[Guest]: Yes, with a weekend break.

01:20:19.760 --> 01:20:20.760
[Unknown]: With a weekend break.

01:20:20.760 --> 01:20:23.680
[Guest]: Where the jury had to go and check their mail.

01:20:23.680 --> 01:20:25.320
[Guest]: So that was that speech.

01:20:25.320 --> 01:20:29.640
[Amit Varma]: And unfortunately, some of the speech, but thankfully not all of it.

01:20:29.640 --> 01:20:30.640
[Amit Varma]: The speech is a book in itself.

01:20:30.640 --> 01:20:34.440
[Amit Varma]: I'll quote a bit from it because I kind of underlined it.

01:20:34.440 --> 01:20:39.140
[Amit Varma]: And I know you don't like people desecrating books, but I underline furiously.

01:20:39.140 --> 01:20:42.200
[Amit Varma]: This is a Tilak speaking as part of his 21 hour speech.

01:20:42.200 --> 01:20:47.200
[Amit Varma]: Quote, if the writer's motives are good, he if he is trying to secure constitutional rights

01:20:47.200 --> 01:20:52.220
[Amit Varma]: for the people trying in a fair way and persevering manner, he is entitled to express his views

01:20:52.220 --> 01:20:53.760
[Amit Varma]: fully and fearlessly.

01:20:53.760 --> 01:20:58.360
[Amit Varma]: The mere fact that the views of the writer are not correct or are even absurd or that

01:20:58.360 --> 01:21:02.320
[Amit Varma]: he expressed them in violent language would not make him seditious.

01:21:02.320 --> 01:21:03.320
[Amit Varma]: Stop quote.

01:21:03.320 --> 01:21:07.320
[Amit Varma]: And I wish a lot of the nationalists of today who sort of seem to revere Tilak would, you

01:21:07.320 --> 01:21:12.280
[Guest]: know, pay a little more attention to his support for free speech.

01:21:12.280 --> 01:21:14.200
[Guest]: So yeah, but that didn't help him.

01:21:14.200 --> 01:21:19.120
[Guest]: The jury was almost all, not almost, it was all white Europeans and Englishmen.

01:21:19.120 --> 01:21:21.120
[Guest]: So whatever he would have done, it was premeditated.

01:21:21.120 --> 01:21:26.480
[Guest]: And in fact, it's very interesting that the judge who tried him was his lawyer when he

01:21:26.480 --> 01:21:27.480
[Guest]: was first convicted.

01:21:27.480 --> 01:21:28.480
[Guest]: Dawar.

01:21:28.480 --> 01:21:29.480
[Guest]: Dawar, this is Dawar.

01:21:29.480 --> 01:21:36.240
[Guest]: This is Dawar was his lawyer when he got bail for Tilak in the first sedition trial.

01:21:36.240 --> 01:21:41.520
[Guest]: And Dawar's son was Tilak's lawyer during his second sedition trial.

01:21:41.520 --> 01:21:44.080
[Amit Varma]: Another man who was involved was Muhammad Ali Jinnah.

01:21:44.080 --> 01:21:45.080
[Amit Varma]: Jinnah was his actual lawyer.

01:21:45.080 --> 01:21:46.840
[Guest]: Was his actual lawyer.

01:21:46.840 --> 01:21:54.360
[Guest]: So and but eventually Tilak had to again argue himself, but so it was all premeditated.

01:21:54.360 --> 01:21:58.520
[Guest]: It was very interesting because Dawar, what he argued to secure bail for Tilak in the

01:21:58.520 --> 01:22:03.920
[Guest]: first trial decided exact opposite in the second trial.

01:22:03.920 --> 01:22:09.800
[Guest]: So it was, you could see the kind of bias or rather the kind of anger against Tilak

01:22:09.800 --> 01:22:11.880
[Guest]: which existed in that day.

01:22:11.880 --> 01:22:14.040
[Guest]: He had become an all powerful figure.

01:22:14.040 --> 01:22:18.800
[Guest]: He was in fact bigger than Gandhi at that point of time or rather Gandhi came later.

01:22:18.800 --> 01:22:21.920
[Unknown]: Gandhi was well known in India.

01:22:21.920 --> 01:22:28.320
[Guest]: He was a giant in South Africa, but Tilak was the giant of the day in 1916.

01:22:28.320 --> 01:22:30.400
[Guest]: So yes, it was again completely political.

01:22:30.400 --> 01:22:32.000
[Guest]: I keep repeating myself.

01:22:32.000 --> 01:22:36.400
[Amit Varma]: And I'm kind of struck by, you know, you quote Dawar's words after Tilak is convicted and

01:22:36.400 --> 01:22:38.640
[Amit Varma]: I'm struck by how vituperative they are.

01:22:38.640 --> 01:22:43.080
[Amit Varma]: Where Dawar says of Tilak, quote, it seems to me that it must be a diseased mind, a most

01:22:43.080 --> 01:22:46.960
[Amit Varma]: perverted intellect that could say that the articles which you have written are legitimate

01:22:46.960 --> 01:22:48.520
[Amit Varma]: weapons in political agitation.

01:22:48.520 --> 01:22:53.200
[Amit Varma]: They are seething with sedition, they preach violence, they speak of murders with approval

01:22:53.200 --> 01:22:57.840
[Amit Varma]: and the cowardly and atrocious act of committing murders with bombs not only seems to meet

01:22:57.840 --> 01:23:02.480
[Amit Varma]: with your approval, but you hail the advent of the bomb in India as if something has come

01:23:02.480 --> 01:23:04.520
[Amit Varma]: to India for his good.

01:23:04.520 --> 01:23:05.520
[Guest]: Stop quote.

01:23:05.520 --> 01:23:06.520
[Guest]: And that's what I said.

01:23:06.520 --> 01:23:10.520
[Guest]: The anger against Tilak was, everyone's minds were prejudiced.

01:23:10.520 --> 01:23:13.960
[Guest]: You couldn't even if you were spoken to 42 hours at a stretch, you still would have been

01:23:13.960 --> 01:23:14.960
[Guest]: convicted.

01:23:14.960 --> 01:23:15.960
[Amit Varma]: It was a 4-1 conclusion.

01:23:15.960 --> 01:23:20.520
[Amit Varma]: And it's it's in sort of an interesting question that kind of strikes me and I think about

01:23:20.520 --> 01:23:22.360
[Amit Varma]: this in other contexts as well.

01:23:22.360 --> 01:23:27.640
[Amit Varma]: That if we are to look back today with the values of today, we would say that, you know,

01:23:27.640 --> 01:23:32.020
[Amit Varma]: the British having a sedition law to prevent people rising up against them is understandable

01:23:32.020 --> 01:23:33.920
[Amit Varma]: and rational from their point of view.

01:23:33.920 --> 01:23:38.720
[Amit Varma]: At the same time, looking back today, we can say that we are completely on Tilak's side

01:23:38.720 --> 01:23:42.200
[Amit Varma]: and the side of all of these people who were fighting the empire, though that qualifies

01:23:42.200 --> 01:23:45.600
[Amit Varma]: as sedition and therefore unlawful at that time.

01:23:45.600 --> 01:23:50.520
[Amit Varma]: But the other aspect of it also, and you know, where Gandhi diverged from the likes of Tilak

01:23:50.520 --> 01:23:51.840
[Amit Varma]: was when it comes to the means.

01:23:51.840 --> 01:23:58.760
[Amit Varma]: Yes, that a lot of these, you know, the Aurobindo Ghosh, Savarkar, to some extent, Tilak in

01:23:58.760 --> 01:24:03.880
[Amit Varma]: his tacit support for violent means seem to say that our end is noble, we want to get

01:24:03.880 --> 01:24:07.920
[Amit Varma]: rid of the empire and therefore any means are justified.

01:24:07.920 --> 01:24:11.440
[Amit Varma]: And to me, even sitting here with this passage of time, it would seem to me that that is

01:24:11.440 --> 01:24:16.880
[Amit Varma]: wrong, that the end doesn't justify the means and that a lot of the moral judgment, if you

01:24:16.880 --> 01:24:21.280
[Amit Varma]: are to pass any on those people has to do with the means also and not the end.

01:24:21.280 --> 01:24:27.720
[Amit Varma]: So the, you know, I'm just thinking that one can't just look at sedition in the classic

01:24:27.720 --> 01:24:31.600
[Amit Varma]: one sided way that of course it is a tool of political oppression.

01:24:31.600 --> 01:24:36.280
[Amit Varma]: But also a you see why it is necessary and be some of the people that the act was being

01:24:36.280 --> 01:24:38.880
[Amit Varma]: used against for basically killing people, they were assassins.

01:24:38.880 --> 01:24:40.240
[Guest]: So let's look at it this way.

01:24:40.240 --> 01:24:44.000
[Guest]: I won't, I'm not saying that one supports murder here or one supports assassinations

01:24:44.000 --> 01:24:45.000
[Guest]: here.

01:24:45.000 --> 01:24:48.760
[Guest]: But you have to look at a way, look at the context of that day, that the government they

01:24:48.760 --> 01:24:53.000
[Guest]: were under, the subjects of whom they were subjects, was not a government of their choice.

01:24:53.000 --> 01:24:54.280
[Guest]: It was imposed on them.

01:24:54.280 --> 01:24:57.440
[Guest]: The laws were imposed on them, the language was imposed on them, the culture was imposed

01:24:57.440 --> 01:24:58.440
[Guest]: on them.

01:24:58.440 --> 01:25:01.960
[Guest]: They completely came and changed Indian society.

01:25:01.960 --> 01:25:07.200
[Guest]: And they looted from India, the famines which happened, they exported grains didn't leave

01:25:07.200 --> 01:25:09.080
[Guest]: anything for the natives.

01:25:09.080 --> 01:25:14.520
[Guest]: So when you look at the anger, what they felt, we will not be able to understand it today.

01:25:14.520 --> 01:25:19.720
[Guest]: So even to try to contextualize it today, I don't know, I don't think we can do that.

01:25:19.720 --> 01:25:23.320
[Amit Varma]: I don't think we are too used to being corseted in a nice democracy.

01:25:23.320 --> 01:25:27.960
[Guest]: And yes, we used to living under rule of law, we are used to checks and balances, it may

01:25:27.960 --> 01:25:29.680
[Guest]: be getting wiped away.

01:25:29.680 --> 01:25:34.040
[Guest]: But today, we are used to that, at that point of time, the rule of law only existed for

01:25:34.040 --> 01:25:35.040
[Amit Varma]: the British.

01:25:35.040 --> 01:25:39.800
[Amit Varma]: Would you say that that situation is analogous to what Kashmir and Kashmiris are going through

01:25:39.800 --> 01:25:40.800
[Unknown]: today?

01:25:40.800 --> 01:25:44.080
[Amit Varma]: Or is it seditious even to bring that thought up?

01:25:44.080 --> 01:25:45.440
[Guest]: That's a very controversial topic.

01:25:45.440 --> 01:25:51.520
[Amit Varma]: But because if we were to say that we would in a sense, we could be accused of sedition.

01:25:51.520 --> 01:25:56.080
[Guest]: But at the same time, yeah, they can try for sure.

01:25:56.080 --> 01:25:59.720
[Guest]: No, but at the end of the day, until unless someone asks someone to pick up arms against

01:25:59.720 --> 01:26:01.400
[Guest]: the government, that's not seditious.

01:26:01.400 --> 01:26:06.440
[Guest]: This is a simple, whenever someone asks me that, oh, is this seditious or not?

01:26:06.440 --> 01:26:09.960
[Guest]: So if someone says, Oh, Amit Verma said this about Kashmir, oh my god, he should be prosecuted

01:26:09.960 --> 01:26:10.960
[Guest]: for sedition.

01:26:10.960 --> 01:26:11.960
[Guest]: I said, did he cause violence?

01:26:11.960 --> 01:26:12.960
[Guest]: Did he bring the state down?

01:26:12.960 --> 01:26:15.240
[Guest]: Or did he try to bring the state down?

01:26:15.240 --> 01:26:17.360
[Amit Varma]: If you did not, it is not seditious.

01:26:17.360 --> 01:26:18.360
[Amit Varma]: Exactly.

01:26:18.360 --> 01:26:21.480
[Amit Varma]: I hope everyone pays heed to these words of yours.

01:26:21.480 --> 01:26:28.160
[Amit Varma]: Let's move on now to sort of the 1970 1918 period where there is on the one hand, you

01:26:28.160 --> 01:26:32.240
[Amit Varma]: have the Montague Jamesford reforms, which are being driven by the British Parliament

01:26:32.240 --> 01:26:36.280
[Amit Varma]: and are largely progressive and good for us and respectful of us.

01:26:36.280 --> 01:26:41.160
[Amit Varma]: But on the other hand, you also have the Rowlett Commission or the Sedition Commission, the

01:26:41.160 --> 01:26:47.200
[Amit Varma]: Sedition Committee, as it is, which is meeting and deciding how to keep the natives in check.

01:26:47.200 --> 01:26:48.720
[Amit Varma]: And what we have isn't adequate.

01:26:48.720 --> 01:26:49.920
[Amit Varma]: What more do we need to do?

01:26:49.920 --> 01:26:55.160
[Amit Varma]: Tell me a bit about you know, what the committee comes up with and the reactions of the Rowlett

01:26:55.160 --> 01:26:56.160
[Guest]: Act.

01:26:56.160 --> 01:27:00.560
[Guest]: So the committee basically goes through one and a half decades of revolutionary crime,

01:27:00.560 --> 01:27:04.720
[Guest]: it chronicles everything and goes to the causes of the crime.

01:27:04.720 --> 01:27:07.720
[Guest]: And then it was supposed to make its recommendation on whether the law should be reformed.

01:27:07.720 --> 01:27:12.480
[Guest]: When I say reform, it should be made stricter to prevent this because you have to understand

01:27:12.480 --> 01:27:17.160
[Guest]: that it also coincided with the First World War in Punjab and in the rest of India, the

01:27:17.160 --> 01:27:19.720
[Guest]: Defense of India Act was in play.

01:27:19.720 --> 01:27:23.960
[Guest]: So they could not have afforded revolution on one hand war on the other.

01:27:23.960 --> 01:27:26.780
[Guest]: So they wanted to prevent this in future.

01:27:26.780 --> 01:27:30.440
[Guest]: So what the Rowlett Committee did, it wanted to make the law stricter.

01:27:30.440 --> 01:27:32.160
[Guest]: It wanted to make the law stricter.

01:27:32.160 --> 01:27:36.960
[Guest]: But ironically, it also built a safety valve in that law.

01:27:36.960 --> 01:27:41.720
[Guest]: It said that this law can only be imposed what they call the Rowlett Act and or the

01:27:41.720 --> 01:27:44.080
[Guest]: Black Act as the Indians called it.

01:27:44.080 --> 01:27:50.760
[Guest]: They wanted it to be imposed only upon a declaration of emergency, a declaration of necessity for

01:27:50.760 --> 01:27:52.360
[Guest]: imposition of such law.

01:27:52.360 --> 01:27:57.920
[Guest]: So that could only be done in cases of uprising and absolute uprising, which was largely not

01:27:57.920 --> 01:28:00.120
[Guest]: accepted by the people.

01:28:00.120 --> 01:28:01.800
[Guest]: In fact, that law was a paper tiger.

01:28:01.800 --> 01:28:04.200
[Guest]: It died a natural death.

01:28:04.200 --> 01:28:06.120
[Guest]: It never came into effect.

01:28:06.120 --> 01:28:10.920
[Guest]: But if you look at the law today, even though we are not under the British government, there

01:28:10.920 --> 01:28:13.840
[Guest]: is no safety valve built into the law.

01:28:13.840 --> 01:28:18.400
[Guest]: It was left to the Supreme Court to finally interpret it.

01:28:18.400 --> 01:28:22.000
[Guest]: And even that interpretation is not being followed today.

01:28:22.000 --> 01:28:26.040
[Guest]: Nobody even the law enforcement officers don't know what this law is actually about.

01:28:26.040 --> 01:28:27.040
[Guest]: And there's no safety valve.

01:28:27.040 --> 01:28:29.600
[Guest]: Even the UAPA does not have any safety valve.

01:28:29.600 --> 01:28:32.720
[Guest]: You can apply this, the police can arrest anyone at any point of time.

01:28:32.720 --> 01:28:36.880
[Guest]: There's no necessity of the situation, let's say in a Chhattisgarh that there's a mass

01:28:36.880 --> 01:28:39.120
[Guest]: uprising, an excited movement all across the state.

01:28:39.120 --> 01:28:41.600
[Guest]: And that's when you impose 124A.

01:28:41.600 --> 01:28:42.760
[Guest]: It's not the case.

01:28:42.760 --> 01:28:47.560
[Guest]: Even in peaceful, you're reading a book in Darjeeling and you say, oh, this shouldn't

01:28:47.560 --> 01:28:52.200
[Guest]: happen and we should have a change of government and there's that and some nice nationalistic

01:28:52.200 --> 01:28:54.200
[Guest]: fellow will come across and say, oh, you're being seditious.

01:28:54.200 --> 01:28:57.680
[Guest]: Yeah, I mean, people have been arrested for Facebook posts.

01:28:57.680 --> 01:29:01.400
[Guest]: They've been arrested for receiving messages on a WhatsApp group, or rather just receiving

01:29:01.400 --> 01:29:04.240
[Guest]: random messages, which they had no nothing to do with.

01:29:04.240 --> 01:29:08.920
[Guest]: So anything, anyone can be just arrested for it.

01:29:08.920 --> 01:29:12.080
[Guest]: So it's not the trial, because I mentioned that they say that there's this, there have

01:29:12.080 --> 01:29:16.920
[Guest]: been two convictions in the last four from 2014, 2016, but there I could not find a single

01:29:16.920 --> 01:29:17.920
[Guest]: conviction.

01:29:17.920 --> 01:29:18.920
[Guest]: I did not find a single judgment.

01:29:18.920 --> 01:29:20.760
[Guest]: So it's not about trial or whatever.

01:29:20.760 --> 01:29:24.080
[Guest]: It's about what happens before that, that arrest and persecution, which happens.

01:29:24.080 --> 01:29:25.080
[Amit Varma]: It's a chilling effect.

01:29:25.080 --> 01:29:26.080
[Amit Varma]: It's a chilling effect.

01:29:26.080 --> 01:29:30.280
[Guest]: Like today, we have to keep giving disclaimers that we're not seditious, right?

01:29:30.280 --> 01:29:31.400
[Guest]: So that is what happens.

01:29:31.400 --> 01:29:34.880
[Guest]: Otherwise, you won't have this fear of speaking to the public about this.

01:29:34.880 --> 01:29:38.400
[Amit Varma]: Someone did once threatened to file a sedition case against me, by the way, in the column

01:29:38.400 --> 01:29:39.400
[Unknown]: about it as well.

01:29:39.400 --> 01:29:40.400
[Guest]: Yeah.

01:29:40.400 --> 01:29:41.400
[Amit Varma]: Oh, wonderful.

01:29:41.400 --> 01:29:43.960
[Amit Varma]: I was in the column against 295A and 153A.

01:29:43.960 --> 01:29:46.760
[Amit Varma]: And somebody said, No, no, you're spreading this affection against the government.

01:29:46.760 --> 01:29:47.760
[Guest]: I'll file a case on 124A.

01:29:47.760 --> 01:29:48.760
[Guest]: Oh, they should have done.

01:29:48.760 --> 01:29:49.760
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, we should have had a why?

01:29:49.760 --> 01:29:52.400
[Amit Varma]: We should have gone up to the Supreme Court to get the law settled again.

01:29:52.400 --> 01:29:55.240
[Amit Varma]: And you won't even defend me because you do bankruptcy law.

01:29:55.240 --> 01:29:57.280
[Amit Varma]: Speaking is very easy, boss.

01:29:57.280 --> 01:29:59.880
[Unknown]: I hope that bankruptcy law is treating you well.

01:29:59.880 --> 01:30:02.000
[Amit Varma]: I'm sure you would have paid me well.

01:30:02.000 --> 01:30:03.000
[Amit Varma]: I don't have any money, bro.

01:30:03.000 --> 01:30:04.000
[Amit Varma]: I'm bankrupt.

01:30:04.000 --> 01:30:08.000
[Amit Varma]: Actually, you know, maybe then you would have come good for me.

01:30:08.000 --> 01:30:13.920
[Amit Varma]: I want to move on now to a chapter of yours called Gandhi, Azad and Nehru, politics of

01:30:13.920 --> 01:30:15.000
[Amit Varma]: sedition.

01:30:15.000 --> 01:30:20.760
[Amit Varma]: And you begin this with a quote by Gandhi, which is in his sedition trial in 1922, which

01:30:20.760 --> 01:30:22.120
[Amit Varma]: I found profoundly impressive.

01:30:22.120 --> 01:30:26.360
[Amit Varma]: So I want to quote the full thing, which is, quote, I would like to state that I entirely

01:30:26.360 --> 01:30:30.400
[Amit Varma]: endorse the learned advocate general's remarks in connection with my humble self.

01:30:30.400 --> 01:30:33.800
[Amit Varma]: I think that he was entirely fair to me in all statements that he has made, because it

01:30:33.800 --> 01:30:34.900
[Amit Varma]: is very true.

01:30:34.900 --> 01:30:37.600
[Amit Varma]: And I have no desire whatsoever to conceal from this court.

01:30:37.600 --> 01:30:42.600
[Amit Varma]: The fact that to preach this affection towards the existing system of government has become

01:30:42.600 --> 01:30:44.400
[Amit Varma]: almost a passion with me.

01:30:44.400 --> 01:30:48.440
[Amit Varma]: And the advocate general is also entirely in the right when he says that my preaching

01:30:48.440 --> 01:30:51.620
[Amit Varma]: of this affection does not commence with my connection to young India.

01:30:51.620 --> 01:30:53.760
[Amit Varma]: This is a magazine Iran.

01:30:53.760 --> 01:30:55.760
[Amit Varma]: But that it can commence much earlier.

01:30:55.760 --> 01:30:58.240
[Amit Varma]: I do not pled any extenuating act.

01:30:58.240 --> 01:31:02.000
[Amit Varma]: I am here, therefore, to invite and submit to the highest penalty that can be inflicted

01:31:02.000 --> 01:31:07.680
[Amit Varma]: upon me for what in law is a deliberate crime and what appears to me the highest duty of

01:31:07.680 --> 01:31:09.400
[Amit Varma]: the citizen, stop quote.

01:31:09.400 --> 01:31:15.360
[Amit Varma]: And your chapter, of course, talks about different trials in which Gandhi, Maulana Abul Kalam

01:31:15.360 --> 01:31:19.160
[Amit Varma]: Azad and Jawaharlal Nehru all pleaded guilty of sedition.

01:31:19.160 --> 01:31:25.560
[Amit Varma]: And when I read, you know, and this sort of this was, you know, all of the courts that

01:31:25.560 --> 01:31:29.040
[Amit Varma]: you've reproduced in this chapter were very clarifying for me, because the thought that

01:31:29.040 --> 01:31:33.400
[Amit Varma]: struck me with your earlier chapter when Tilak and all these guys were under trial, is that

01:31:33.400 --> 01:31:35.280
[Amit Varma]: why were they defending themselves?

01:31:35.280 --> 01:31:39.000
[Amit Varma]: They were guilty of sedition and they should just stand up proud and say that, yeah, of

01:31:39.000 --> 01:31:40.240
[Amit Varma]: course, I am disaffected.

01:31:40.240 --> 01:31:44.240
[Amit Varma]: I am preaching this affection, you know, so what is the crime?

01:31:44.240 --> 01:31:47.360
[Amit Varma]: And Gandhi, Azad and Nehru actually do this.

01:31:47.360 --> 01:31:53.120
[Amit Varma]: And they are all people who are protesting against the British by peaceful means using

01:31:53.120 --> 01:31:56.200
[Amit Varma]: non cooperation and civil disobedience and so on.

01:31:56.200 --> 01:32:02.840
[Amit Varma]: And this sort of refreshing honesty owning up to what is quote unquote a crime, you know,

01:32:02.840 --> 01:32:05.320
[Amit Varma]: seems to bring a moral force to the freedom struggle.

01:32:05.320 --> 01:32:10.440
[Guest]: See, this has a lot to do with the change in strategy, I would call it.

01:32:10.440 --> 01:32:17.480
[Guest]: The Tilak of 1897 and the Tilak of 1916 did not want a British free India.

01:32:17.480 --> 01:32:20.000
[Guest]: They did not want freedom as such.

01:32:20.000 --> 01:32:26.240
[Guest]: They wanted the power to govern themselves within the Commonwealth, within under the

01:32:26.240 --> 01:32:30.360
[Guest]: patronage of the crown, dominion status, autonomous status.

01:32:30.360 --> 01:32:34.120
[Guest]: They never in their life at that point of time had imagined that India could be completely

01:32:34.120 --> 01:32:35.740
[Guest]: free of the British.

01:32:35.740 --> 01:32:40.800
[Guest]: So this Poon Swaraj thing which happened with Tilak and when he coined the term Swaraj is

01:32:40.800 --> 01:32:42.600
[Guest]: my birthright and I'll have it.

01:32:42.600 --> 01:32:47.080
[Guest]: That happened later that not happened even at the time of a second trial, right?

01:32:47.080 --> 01:32:54.680
[Guest]: So there was a shift in the Indian political scenario after 1919 when Gandhi came here.

01:32:54.680 --> 01:32:58.040
[Guest]: When and Gandhi in fact had become very unpopular, which I talked about just before his sedition

01:32:58.040 --> 01:33:01.400
[Guest]: trial, he had become very unpopular for calling off the civil disobedience movement because

01:33:01.400 --> 01:33:05.680
[Guest]: of because of Chori Chori called it off and the people were very disillusioned.

01:33:05.680 --> 01:33:09.240
[Guest]: In fact, if the British wouldn't have prosecuted him, maybe the Gandhi that we know of today

01:33:09.240 --> 01:33:10.840
[Guest]: wouldn't have existed.

01:33:10.840 --> 01:33:13.600
[Guest]: Maybe we wouldn't have assumed the kind of relevance that he did after that.

01:33:13.600 --> 01:33:14.600
[Guest]: Streisand effect.

01:33:14.600 --> 01:33:15.600
[Guest]: Yes.

01:33:15.600 --> 01:33:16.600
[Guest]: So, exactly.

01:33:16.600 --> 01:33:20.320
[Guest]: So we should maybe call it the Gandhi effect.

01:33:20.320 --> 01:33:23.240
[Guest]: So basically what they did was they wanted complete freedom.

01:33:23.240 --> 01:33:25.160
[Guest]: They wanted Indians to govern India.

01:33:25.160 --> 01:33:27.040
[Guest]: They wanted Indians to frame their own laws.

01:33:27.040 --> 01:33:30.480
[Guest]: They didn't want laws from England to run the country here.

01:33:30.480 --> 01:33:34.760
[Guest]: So what they did was they said that I refuse to recognize the law.

01:33:34.760 --> 01:33:36.560
[Guest]: They say fine, this is sedition.

01:33:36.560 --> 01:33:37.880
[Guest]: If you say it is sedition, it is sedition.

01:33:37.880 --> 01:33:39.440
[Guest]: I refuse to recognize it.

01:33:39.440 --> 01:33:43.480
[Guest]: Gandhi called it the prince of political offenses, right?

01:33:43.480 --> 01:33:48.600
[Guest]: So what they did was they said, I refuse to recognize your authority over me.

01:33:48.600 --> 01:33:51.160
[Guest]: If you say it is sedition, fine, then I am seditious.

01:33:51.160 --> 01:33:52.160
[Guest]: I have done it.

01:33:52.160 --> 01:33:53.200
[Guest]: You punish me for it.

01:33:53.200 --> 01:33:55.400
[Guest]: And all of them asked for punishment.

01:33:55.400 --> 01:33:56.400
[Guest]: Nobody said, let me go.

01:33:56.400 --> 01:33:58.360
[Guest]: They said, give me the maximum punishment possible.

01:33:58.360 --> 01:34:02.160
[Guest]: Gandhi, in fact, said when they said that Tilak got six years, so you should also get

01:34:02.160 --> 01:34:03.160
[Guest]: six years.

01:34:03.160 --> 01:34:07.040
[Guest]: Gandhi said he was privileged to be equated with Tilak for getting six years.

01:34:07.040 --> 01:34:09.120
[Guest]: Nehru simply went up to the magistrate and said, you punish me.

01:34:09.120 --> 01:34:10.640
[Guest]: I don't even want to fight you.

01:34:10.640 --> 01:34:11.640
[Guest]: There shouldn't be any trial.

01:34:11.640 --> 01:34:12.640
[Guest]: I'm admitting to everything.

01:34:12.640 --> 01:34:13.640
[Guest]: The magistrate said, please don't do this.

01:34:13.640 --> 01:34:14.640
[Guest]: He said, please don't do this.

01:34:14.640 --> 01:34:15.640
[Guest]: I'll get you out of it.

01:34:15.640 --> 01:34:20.640
[Guest]: And he said, I'll make sure you don't have to face any prison.

01:34:20.640 --> 01:34:23.480
[Guest]: Nehru said, thank you so much, but I don't want it.

01:34:23.480 --> 01:34:25.040
[Amit Varma]: I want the maximum penalty.

01:34:25.040 --> 01:34:29.960
[Amit Varma]: And I want to quote something that Nehru says about the Congress here, which of course,

01:34:29.960 --> 01:34:33.600
[Amit Varma]: the Congress then was a very, very different beast from what it is today.

01:34:33.600 --> 01:34:37.840
[Amit Varma]: But quote, in the Congress, we have nothing to do with loyalty.

01:34:37.840 --> 01:34:41.000
[Amit Varma]: We are disloyal and it is our business to preach this loyalty.

01:34:41.000 --> 01:34:44.440
[Amit Varma]: Are you going to be loyal to those people who humiliate your people, who degrade your

01:34:44.440 --> 01:34:48.280
[Amit Varma]: country, or are you going to be loyal to your own country, to your own people?

01:34:48.280 --> 01:34:52.400
[Amit Varma]: Indian nationalism and British imperialism are at close grips with each other.

01:34:52.400 --> 01:34:55.920
[Amit Varma]: British imperialism may succeed in suppressing Indian nationalism.

01:34:55.920 --> 01:35:00.880
[Amit Varma]: But remember this also, that while Indian nationalism will grow again, but British imperialism

01:35:00.880 --> 01:35:04.400
[Amit Varma]: will be suppressed once and for all by Indian nationalism.

01:35:04.400 --> 01:35:05.400
[Amit Varma]: Stop quote.

01:35:05.400 --> 01:35:08.880
[Amit Varma]: And a lot of the people who are talking rubbish about Nehru today should, you know, really

01:35:08.880 --> 01:35:10.800
[Guest]: read up a little more on the sort of moral.

01:35:10.800 --> 01:35:13.520
[Guest]: One man almost spent 10 years in jail.

01:35:13.520 --> 01:35:16.440
[Guest]: He was in jail when his wife was in on her deathbed.

01:35:16.440 --> 01:35:20.200
[Guest]: In fact, he was only released because she was very sick.

01:35:20.200 --> 01:35:23.680
[Guest]: His father was in his deathbed when he got arrested when he came back to Allahabad and

01:35:23.680 --> 01:35:26.320
[Guest]: they made that speech for which he eventually got arrested.

01:35:26.320 --> 01:35:32.080
[Guest]: His father was unwell and his father was unwell because he had been arrested previously and

01:35:32.080 --> 01:35:34.000
[Amit Varma]: he also refused to defend himself.

01:35:34.000 --> 01:35:35.560
[Amit Varma]: They spent their lives getting arrested.

01:35:35.560 --> 01:35:36.560
[Guest]: Yes, they were in.

01:35:36.560 --> 01:35:38.200
[Guest]: He was in prison for about 10 years.

01:35:38.200 --> 01:35:42.640
[Guest]: His wife was in prison, mother went to prison and his father went to prison.

01:35:42.640 --> 01:35:45.880
[Guest]: Everyone at that point of time went to prison and they were proud of it.

01:35:45.880 --> 01:35:54.000
[Amit Varma]: I mean, I must say this, you know, a lot of people sort of look at people like Nehru and

01:35:54.000 --> 01:35:58.040
[Amit Varma]: Savarkar in very binary points of view that one is good and the other is evil.

01:35:58.040 --> 01:36:00.560
[Amit Varma]: And I'd say there are, it's more complicated than that.

01:36:00.560 --> 01:36:04.320
[Amit Varma]: For example, it often comes up on Twitter that, hey Savarkar, apologize to the British

01:36:04.320 --> 01:36:06.800
[Amit Varma]: and you contrast that with what Nehru is doing now.

01:36:06.800 --> 01:36:10.680
[Amit Varma]: But it is also true that Savarkar went to the cellular jail in Andaman, known as Kalapani,

01:36:10.680 --> 01:36:15.080
[Amit Varma]: where the sort of tortures inflicted on him were beyond anything, any other.

01:36:15.080 --> 01:36:17.640
[Guest]: And not just physical torture, mental torture.

01:36:17.640 --> 01:36:23.720
[Guest]: Damodar Savarkar talks about it when in their stories, it's clearly mentioned this man,

01:36:23.720 --> 01:36:26.440
[Guest]: he would, he would swallow himself standing up.

01:36:26.440 --> 01:36:27.680
[Guest]: He lost control of his bowels.

01:36:27.680 --> 01:36:30.800
[Guest]: Yeah, they weren't allowed to go to the, they weren't allowed.

01:36:30.800 --> 01:36:31.800
[Amit Varma]: This is really the smallest.

01:36:31.800 --> 01:36:32.800
[Guest]: They were allowed to clean themselves.

01:36:32.800 --> 01:36:33.800
[Guest]: Yeah.

01:36:33.800 --> 01:36:35.560
[Guest]: And they were supposed to toil in the sun.

01:36:35.560 --> 01:36:39.800
[Guest]: If you've been to the Andaman, you'll realize how harsh that sun is.

01:36:39.800 --> 01:36:43.720
[Guest]: And their cells were, the cells were so small.

01:36:43.720 --> 01:36:48.680
[Guest]: As it's, I know some hotel rooms nowadays are very small, but it was even smaller than

01:36:48.680 --> 01:36:49.680
[Guest]: that.

01:36:49.680 --> 01:36:50.680
[Guest]: You couldn't stand up properly.

01:36:50.680 --> 01:36:51.680
[Amit Varma]: You had to be bent all the time.

01:36:51.680 --> 01:36:55.320
[Amit Varma]: In fact, the two recent biographies of Savarkar by Vaibhav Varadhan and Vikram Sampath both

01:36:55.320 --> 01:36:56.560
[Amit Varma]: deal with this at some length.

01:36:56.560 --> 01:37:01.560
[Amit Varma]: And you can go to the prison diaries of Savarkar himself and other people who were imprisoned

01:37:01.560 --> 01:37:03.400
[Amit Varma]: with him to see how bad it was.

01:37:03.400 --> 01:37:06.440
[Amit Varma]: So I would just say that we shouldn't always rush to judgment.

01:37:06.440 --> 01:37:10.720
[Amit Varma]: I think Savarkar did some truly despicable things and gave rise to despicable ways of

01:37:10.720 --> 01:37:15.600
[Amit Varma]: thinking in the twenties onwards, especially with his horrendously bad book Hindutva.

01:37:15.600 --> 01:37:20.360
[Amit Varma]: But at the same time, had he died in 1910, he'd probably be remembered as a hero today.

01:37:20.360 --> 01:37:21.360
[Guest]: Absolutely.

01:37:21.360 --> 01:37:26.160
[Guest]: Because what he did in England, he set up India House there, the revolutionary activity

01:37:26.160 --> 01:37:27.160
[Guest]: in England.

01:37:27.160 --> 01:37:28.720
[Guest]: He sent pamphlets from there to Bombay.

01:37:28.720 --> 01:37:31.800
[Guest]: So both the brothers had a huge role to play at that point of time.

01:37:31.800 --> 01:37:35.800
[Guest]: It's only after Kala Pani that the politics changed.

01:37:35.800 --> 01:37:40.280
[Guest]: And I don't really, I may be criticized for this, but I don't really blame him for writing

01:37:40.280 --> 01:37:42.560
[Guest]: a letter, a mercy petition.

01:37:42.560 --> 01:37:43.560
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, I would do the same.

01:37:43.560 --> 01:37:45.720
[Amit Varma]: I would do the absolute same thing.

01:37:45.720 --> 01:37:46.720
[Amit Varma]: The kind of suffering.

01:37:46.720 --> 01:37:51.760
[Amit Varma]: I mean, Gandhi, Nehru and all these people were basic, they were treated in a very civil

01:37:51.760 --> 01:37:52.760
[Guest]: way.

01:37:52.760 --> 01:37:53.760
[Guest]: They were treated with a lot of respect.

01:37:53.760 --> 01:37:57.040
[Guest]: They had access to books, they had access to visitors.

01:37:57.040 --> 01:37:58.440
[Guest]: They had, they could write letters.

01:37:58.440 --> 01:38:00.600
[Guest]: Nehru wrote his books while in prison.

01:38:00.600 --> 01:38:05.360
[Unknown]: I mean, it was the only way he could have written, or maybe today people could write,

01:38:05.360 --> 01:38:07.720
[Guest]: but maybe we should throw some people in prison for them to write.

01:38:07.720 --> 01:38:12.480
[Amit Varma]: And you know, I have a huge amount of criticisms of Nehru for his economic policies post independence.

01:38:12.480 --> 01:38:16.040
[Amit Varma]: But the point is, all these people contain multitudes and we should remember before we

01:38:16.040 --> 01:38:17.480
[Amit Varma]: rush to judgment.

01:38:17.480 --> 01:38:21.000
[Guest]: That's why I said that this access to history is very important.

01:38:21.000 --> 01:38:22.960
[Guest]: That we need to understand this.

01:38:22.960 --> 01:38:26.160
[Guest]: I did not know half of all this when I was researching.

01:38:26.160 --> 01:38:31.760
[Guest]: It's only after I read all this that I understood the context of the actions back then.

01:38:31.760 --> 01:38:35.280
[Amit Varma]: So we have to wind up in 20 minutes before you have a flight to catch.

01:38:35.280 --> 01:38:40.960
[Amit Varma]: So I want to move on from Gandhi, Nehru and Azad and talk about two sort of important

01:38:40.960 --> 01:38:46.480
[Amit Varma]: cases just on the cusp of India getting independence, where important judgments were made regarding

01:38:46.480 --> 01:38:47.480
[Amit Varma]: 124 A.N.

01:38:47.480 --> 01:38:53.040
[Amit Varma]: One of them is Niharendu Dutt Majumdar versus the King Emperor, which is administered by

01:38:53.040 --> 01:38:57.760
[Amit Varma]: the federal court, the sort of predecessor to the Supreme Court.

01:38:57.760 --> 01:38:59.200
[Amit Varma]: And this is a very interesting judgment.

01:38:59.200 --> 01:39:00.200
[Guest]: Tell me why.

01:39:00.200 --> 01:39:05.200
[Guest]: So basically, that's when the court created a distinction between mere speech, seditious

01:39:05.200 --> 01:39:09.520
[Guest]: speech as they call it, and actually inciting violence.

01:39:09.520 --> 01:39:15.000
[Guest]: So sedition as it was understood more or less remained the same from bongo bashi to tilak

01:39:15.000 --> 01:39:16.600
[Guest]: to the 1940s.

01:39:16.600 --> 01:39:18.520
[Guest]: The interpretation did not change.

01:39:18.520 --> 01:39:23.680
[Guest]: For the first time, Justice Mori Squire, he brought in the interpretation which we today

01:39:23.680 --> 01:39:29.520
[Guest]: rely upon eventually in the Indian Supreme Court also interpreted the same way that mere

01:39:29.520 --> 01:39:35.680
[Guest]: criticism is not seditious until and unless it causes violence.

01:39:35.680 --> 01:39:39.240
[Guest]: So just speaking simply, this is what he said.

01:39:39.240 --> 01:39:45.080
[Guest]: And eventually it had to be set aside because the criminal justice system of the day and

01:39:45.080 --> 01:39:49.040
[Guest]: the politicians of the day thought that this man is ruining everything for us.

01:39:49.040 --> 01:39:52.760
[Guest]: It was set aside eventually and the old system was again destroyed in the second case.

01:39:52.760 --> 01:39:57.840
[Amit Varma]: And the other case you talk about is the Privy Council judgment of 1947, which sort of takes

01:39:57.840 --> 01:39:58.840
[Amit Varma]: the opposite view.

01:39:58.840 --> 01:40:01.840
[Guest]: Yes, because they said that Squire is wrong.

01:40:01.840 --> 01:40:04.520
[Guest]: He's gone beyond what is written in the statute.

01:40:04.520 --> 01:40:06.360
[Guest]: And you should just stick to what the statute says.

01:40:06.360 --> 01:40:11.600
[Amit Varma]: And all of this has bearing, you know, there's also a drama playing out when the Indian Constitution

01:40:11.600 --> 01:40:17.320
[Amit Varma]: is being written, because, you know, for example, what should our free speech laws be like,

01:40:17.320 --> 01:40:19.280
[Amit Varma]: how much free speech should be guaranteed.

01:40:19.280 --> 01:40:21.960
[Amit Varma]: And there are sort of debates about this.

01:40:21.960 --> 01:40:27.800
[Amit Varma]: Some people are arguing for, you know, the like, US style free speech, where, you know,

01:40:27.800 --> 01:40:31.980
[Amit Varma]: which I also am broadly in agreement with where it's more or less absolute.

01:40:31.980 --> 01:40:35.680
[Amit Varma]: And others are saying that no, we need caveats and the questions come up, what should the

01:40:35.680 --> 01:40:37.200
[Amit Varma]: caveats be?

01:40:37.200 --> 01:40:45.280
[Amit Varma]: And there's a fierce argument about whether the word sedition should be one of the restrictions.

01:40:45.280 --> 01:40:46.960
[Guest]: Tell me a bit about that and how that pans out.

01:40:46.960 --> 01:40:51.100
[Guest]: So the first draft of Article 19 today was originally Article 13.

01:40:51.100 --> 01:40:54.920
[Guest]: And one of the restrictions on free speech back then was seditious speech.

01:40:54.920 --> 01:40:59.520
[Guest]: So it was supposed to be it wouldn't have been protected by the fundamental right to

01:40:59.520 --> 01:41:01.160
[Guest]: freedom of speech and expression.

01:41:01.160 --> 01:41:05.920
[Guest]: So that's when certain people in the Constituent Assembly and on the Fundamental Rights Subcommittee

01:41:05.920 --> 01:41:07.400
[Guest]: opposed this.

01:41:07.400 --> 01:41:11.760
[Guest]: They said that Patel is framing this from the point of view of a constable.

01:41:11.760 --> 01:41:16.280
[Guest]: Because the very translating that means that someone has to maintain law and order the

01:41:16.280 --> 01:41:20.080
[Guest]: constable or the lowest police officer is responsible for maintenance of law and order.

01:41:20.080 --> 01:41:21.080
[Guest]: This is Somnath Lahiri.

01:41:21.080 --> 01:41:23.040
[Guest]: Somnath Lahiri who said this.

01:41:23.040 --> 01:41:29.760
[Guest]: And Munshi talks about how this how his father and his grandfather, they were punished for

01:41:29.760 --> 01:41:33.840
[Guest]: sedition and now this is being imposed on citizens in the Constitution.

01:41:33.840 --> 01:41:40.300
[Guest]: So there is a quietly it was just removed from the restrictions on free speech by Patel.

01:41:40.300 --> 01:41:45.200
[Guest]: But it reappeared again and again faced huge criticism from the Constituent Assembly from

01:41:45.200 --> 01:41:46.200
[Guest]: a lot of people.

01:41:46.200 --> 01:41:48.040
[Amit Varma]: So it was eventually removed from the.

01:41:48.040 --> 01:41:51.480
[Amit Varma]: And the interesting thing is that if it was eventually removed, you would assume that

01:41:51.480 --> 01:41:57.520
[Amit Varma]: 124A would also go because what basically happened, put simply, correct me if I'm wrong,

01:41:57.520 --> 01:42:00.640
[Amit Varma]: is that we took the entire IPC as it was.

01:42:00.640 --> 01:42:04.800
[Amit Varma]: And we basically said that whatever in it is contradictory to something in our Constitution

01:42:04.800 --> 01:42:06.320
[Amit Varma]: is immediately repealed.

01:42:06.320 --> 01:42:08.160
[Amit Varma]: Otherwise it stays as it is.

01:42:08.160 --> 01:42:12.680
[Amit Varma]: So the assumption was that because of word sedition has been removed from Article 19,

01:42:12.680 --> 01:42:18.200
[Amit Varma]: that therefore the sedition law, which is 124A will also cease to be active.

01:42:18.200 --> 01:42:22.360
[Amit Varma]: And that in fact, an early ruling was to that effect.

01:42:22.360 --> 01:42:26.520
[Amit Varma]: But then the First Amendment we made to our Constitution changed all that.

01:42:26.520 --> 01:42:31.840
[Guest]: So basically what the courts did was they gave the blessing to the law.

01:42:31.840 --> 01:42:39.360
[Guest]: And they in fact went back to the interpretation given pre-independence interpretation given.

01:42:39.360 --> 01:42:45.520
[Guest]: So it actually made the situation even worse than what the Assembly feared that was what

01:42:45.520 --> 01:42:47.120
[Guest]: was happening.

01:42:47.120 --> 01:42:53.240
[Guest]: Because early India, early democratic India was not able to actually, they were still

01:42:53.240 --> 01:42:55.920
[Guest]: fearful that hangover was still there.

01:42:55.920 --> 01:43:00.720
[Guest]: They still felt that people because they had just seen a anti-establishment movement, they

01:43:00.720 --> 01:43:03.320
[Guest]: still felt that people still have those tendencies within them.

01:43:03.320 --> 01:43:04.320
[Amit Varma]: Maybe that's why.

01:43:04.320 --> 01:43:09.680
[Amit Varma]: And I did an episode with the historian Gyan Prakash and he spoke about how when the framers

01:43:09.680 --> 01:43:13.640
[Amit Varma]: of the Constitution were in that locked room, sort of framing the Constitution, there was

01:43:13.640 --> 01:43:15.280
[Amit Varma]: violence all across the country outside.

01:43:15.280 --> 01:43:17.800
[Guest]: It was by no means a given that we will stay one nation.

01:43:17.800 --> 01:43:19.880
[Amit Varma]: They just come out of the partition violence.

01:43:19.880 --> 01:43:26.360
[Amit Varma]: Can you see the context of violence 1857, then the revolutions of the post Bengal splitting

01:43:26.360 --> 01:43:32.480
[Amit Varma]: the sort of early 20th century and now again the post partition violence and that is determining

01:43:32.480 --> 01:43:34.680
[Guest]: how draconian the laws are.

01:43:34.680 --> 01:43:39.180
[Guest]: Because then the violence was not a nationalistic in nature, it became religious.

01:43:39.180 --> 01:43:42.080
[Guest]: So they had still had that fear.

01:43:42.080 --> 01:43:45.760
[Guest]: Every government has that fear that it will be overthrown not maybe for political reasons,

01:43:45.760 --> 01:43:47.260
[Guest]: but maybe for religious reasons.

01:43:47.260 --> 01:43:49.920
[Guest]: So that is why they allowed the law to exist on the books.

01:43:49.920 --> 01:43:54.720
[Amit Varma]: So now let's get to this seminal case called Kedarnath Singh versus State of Bihar.

01:43:54.720 --> 01:43:57.760
[Amit Varma]: As you pointed out earlier, what happens with the First Amendment is that one of the caveats

01:43:57.760 --> 01:44:03.040
[Amit Varma]: introduced is public order and the courts therefore now begin to argue about whether

01:44:03.040 --> 01:44:08.700
[Amit Varma]: the introduction of this caveat means that the sedition law is constitutional after all.

01:44:08.700 --> 01:44:12.520
[Amit Varma]: And you basically have the Patna High Court saying that 124A is constitutional.

01:44:12.520 --> 01:44:15.480
[Amit Varma]: The Manipur High Court says it's partly unconstitutional.

01:44:15.480 --> 01:44:19.520
[Amit Varma]: The Allahabad High Court finds it to be completely unconstitutional.

01:44:19.520 --> 01:44:22.720
[Amit Varma]: And then comes Kedarnath Singh versus State of Bihar.

01:44:22.720 --> 01:44:28.240
[Guest]: So the politics of the time, the Communist Party of India was quite popular and quite

01:44:28.240 --> 01:44:33.740
[Guest]: powerful and we were at a time where the Congress was the largest party and the second largest

01:44:33.740 --> 01:44:35.640
[Guest]: party was the Communist Party.

01:44:35.640 --> 01:44:42.720
[Guest]: And in Bihar, this gentleman delivered a speech where he called police the dogs of CID and

01:44:42.720 --> 01:44:47.200
[Guest]: said that he was spoken in the bureaucracy.

01:44:47.200 --> 01:44:51.880
[Guest]: So he was arrested for sedition under the Congress government and he was arrested for

01:44:51.880 --> 01:44:52.880
[Guest]: sedition.

01:44:52.880 --> 01:44:54.640
[Guest]: So eventually when the court and he was convicted for it as well.

01:44:54.640 --> 01:44:55.800
[Guest]: And this was not the only case.

01:44:55.800 --> 01:44:59.040
[Guest]: This was actually a batch of matters from UP and Bihar.

01:44:59.040 --> 01:45:03.640
[Guest]: And when these matters eventually reached the Supreme Court, what the Supreme Court

01:45:03.640 --> 01:45:10.400
[Guest]: held which applies till date is that till that time, even though they went back to Morris

01:45:10.400 --> 01:45:18.680
[Guest]: Goir's interpretation in Niranjan Dutta and they simply said that public order, if there

01:45:18.680 --> 01:45:23.880
[Guest]: is a restriction on public order on free speech, that means that there has to be public disorder

01:45:23.880 --> 01:45:27.760
[Guest]: for that speech to be seditious.

01:45:27.760 --> 01:45:34.960
[Guest]: As long as public order is not disturbed, that speech cannot be curtailed.

01:45:34.960 --> 01:45:37.420
[Guest]: So public disorder means violence.

01:45:37.420 --> 01:45:41.800
[Guest]: It means just disturbing the status quo somewhere causing law and order problems.

01:45:41.800 --> 01:45:49.120
[Guest]: So till the time a writing or a play or a movie or a speech does not incite violence

01:45:49.120 --> 01:45:55.440
[Guest]: or public disorder or have the tendency of doing that, that test has to be there for

01:45:55.440 --> 01:45:58.280
[Guest]: anything to be declared as seditious.

01:45:58.280 --> 01:46:03.920
[Guest]: So very simply put that today, if I say something and that causes people to take up arms against

01:46:03.920 --> 01:46:09.240
[Guest]: the government or it may cause people to take up arms against the government, any such thing

01:46:09.240 --> 01:46:14.480
[Guest]: will not be seditious till the time that test is met, that it can cause violence or incite

01:46:14.480 --> 01:46:15.480
[Guest]: violence against the state.

01:46:15.480 --> 01:46:19.680
[Guest]: Because you have to understand, it's not just violence against a community or violence against

01:46:19.680 --> 01:46:23.820
[Guest]: a group of or of a political party.

01:46:23.820 --> 01:46:27.380
[Guest]: The law is categorized under the offense of against the state.

01:46:27.380 --> 01:46:34.080
[Guest]: So it has to be by that very, very simple logic, it has to be violence against the state

01:46:34.080 --> 01:46:36.120
[Guest]: and the state today is all powerful.

01:46:36.120 --> 01:46:38.720
[Guest]: 20 individuals cannot overthrow the state.

01:46:38.720 --> 01:46:41.240
[Guest]: A thousand individuals cannot overthrow the state.

01:46:41.240 --> 01:46:43.000
[Guest]: The state is not brittle today.

01:46:43.000 --> 01:46:49.200
[Guest]: So what that judgment did was that it introduced that test of violence being caused or likelihood

01:46:49.200 --> 01:46:50.900
[Guest]: of violence to be caused.

01:46:50.900 --> 01:46:54.600
[Guest]: But unfortunately it is not being followed in spirit.

01:46:54.600 --> 01:46:59.480
[Amit Varma]: In fact, a lot of people don't even know many aspects of the procedural implications of

01:46:59.480 --> 01:47:00.480
[Amit Varma]: 124A.

01:47:00.480 --> 01:47:03.880
[Amit Varma]: Like one of the ways in which you point out it has evolved is, for example, in the state

01:47:03.880 --> 01:47:09.400
[Amit Varma]: of Maharashtra, you know, it's not enough for someone to say file a case of sedition

01:47:09.400 --> 01:47:10.480
[Amit Varma]: against me.

01:47:10.480 --> 01:47:15.520
[Amit Varma]: It has to also be approved by the government of the day before I can be hauled into court.

01:47:15.520 --> 01:47:20.120
[Amit Varma]: But many constable level police inspector level cops don't actually know this.

01:47:20.120 --> 01:47:24.680
[Amit Varma]: And therefore the sedition law has become a tool of harassment.

01:47:24.680 --> 01:47:29.800
[Guest]: In fact, in all of India, only Maharashtra has these guidelines.

01:47:29.800 --> 01:47:34.240
[Guest]: And these guidelines also arise out of a court case when Asim Trivedi was being prosecuted

01:47:34.240 --> 01:47:36.240
[Guest]: for sedition after he drew those cartoons.

01:47:36.240 --> 01:47:37.240
[Guest]: 2014, I think.

01:47:37.240 --> 01:47:38.240
[Guest]: Yes.

01:47:38.240 --> 01:47:40.760
[Guest]: So the court simply said it may be distasteful.

01:47:40.760 --> 01:47:43.240
[Guest]: You may not like it, but that does not make it seditious.

01:47:43.240 --> 01:47:45.000
[Guest]: It did not incite any violence.

01:47:45.000 --> 01:47:46.000
[Guest]: Nothing happened.

01:47:46.000 --> 01:47:48.220
[Guest]: So why is he in jail for sedition?

01:47:48.220 --> 01:47:49.840
[Guest]: So they set down guidelines.

01:47:49.840 --> 01:47:55.360
[Guest]: They said that a person cannot even be arrested for under section 124A till the time there

01:47:55.360 --> 01:47:59.960
[Guest]: is a written opinion of a law officer and the investigation has to be done by a senior

01:47:59.960 --> 01:48:02.880
[Guest]: police officer among many other things.

01:48:02.880 --> 01:48:04.640
[Guest]: So it laid down these guidelines.

01:48:04.640 --> 01:48:07.440
[Guest]: Other than Maharashtra, no other state has these guidelines.

01:48:07.440 --> 01:48:14.800
[Guest]: Even when a PIL was filed in the Supreme Court saying that you have to enforce Kedarnath,

01:48:14.800 --> 01:48:16.320
[Guest]: the court simply said follow Kedarnath.

01:48:16.320 --> 01:48:19.040
[Guest]: It did not lay down any guidelines again.

01:48:19.040 --> 01:48:23.880
[Guest]: So today what situation is that across the country, there is no sanction required for

01:48:23.880 --> 01:48:24.880
[Guest]: arrest.

01:48:24.880 --> 01:48:28.200
[Guest]: A sanction is only required when a charge sheet is to be filed and charges are to be

01:48:28.200 --> 01:48:29.800
[Guest]: framed against you.

01:48:29.800 --> 01:48:31.400
[Guest]: But prior to that, there is no sanction required.

01:48:31.400 --> 01:48:34.520
[Guest]: Otherwise, it's required under 196 of CRPC.

01:48:34.520 --> 01:48:37.320
[Guest]: So to arrest someone for sedition is very easy.

01:48:37.320 --> 01:48:41.920
[Guest]: To fire a person to go to court and get a fire registered for sedition is very easy.

01:48:41.920 --> 01:48:48.360
[Guest]: So what I spoke about here to build a safety wall here as well is that create a provision

01:48:48.360 --> 01:48:53.000
[Guest]: or create a or at least issue guidelines across it should be by from the central government

01:48:53.000 --> 01:48:59.880
[Guest]: to all the states that even to arrest someone under 124A, you need prior sanction or the

01:48:59.880 --> 01:49:04.400
[Guest]: approval of a high ranking or IG, DG level police officer without a can't even arrest

01:49:04.400 --> 01:49:05.400
[Guest]: someone for sedition.

01:49:05.400 --> 01:49:07.840
[Amit Varma]: And the argument is that we do have other laws like UAPA.

01:49:07.840 --> 01:49:09.880
[Guest]: So we don't really need which is a very stringent law.

01:49:09.880 --> 01:49:11.240
[Amit Varma]: It is a draconian law in itself.

01:49:11.240 --> 01:49:12.320
[Amit Varma]: We should go by itself.

01:49:12.320 --> 01:49:14.560
[Amit Varma]: But you're saying it's a political reality is there to stay.

01:49:14.560 --> 01:49:17.120
[Amit Varma]: So why not at least do away with sedition?

01:49:17.120 --> 01:49:19.240
[Amit Varma]: So you know, we'll have to wind up soon.

01:49:19.240 --> 01:49:21.520
[Amit Varma]: So I'll have one final sort of question for you.

01:49:21.520 --> 01:49:23.600
[Amit Varma]: And I'd urge all the listeners to read the book.

01:49:23.600 --> 01:49:28.360
[Amit Varma]: And if we focused on the historical aspect of it so far, that's what the book also does

01:49:28.360 --> 01:49:31.960
[Amit Varma]: extremely well, and which is extremely important.

01:49:31.960 --> 01:49:36.280
[Amit Varma]: But to read the later chapters about how the sedition law is in modern times, do read the

01:49:36.280 --> 01:49:37.280
[Amit Varma]: book.

01:49:37.280 --> 01:49:40.560
[Amit Varma]: My question to you is this and here I will be slightly mischievous.

01:49:40.560 --> 01:49:45.360
[Amit Varma]: And I will invert Mr. Tilak's argument and use it against the law which was used to imprison

01:49:45.360 --> 01:49:50.360
[Amit Varma]: him, which is Tilak's argument back in the day when the age of consent law was passed,

01:49:50.360 --> 01:49:55.160
[Amit Varma]: was that look, this is a necessary law, but society is not ready for it.

01:49:55.160 --> 01:49:56.160
[Amit Varma]: Most people agree with this.

01:49:56.160 --> 01:49:57.600
[Amit Varma]: So change has to happen gradually.

01:49:57.600 --> 01:49:59.520
[Amit Varma]: It cannot be imposed top down.

01:49:59.520 --> 01:50:06.320
[Amit Varma]: Now in the modern time, you and I are sort of elite liberals who don't believe in all

01:50:06.320 --> 01:50:10.280
[Amit Varma]: of these free speech laws like 124A, 153A, 295A.

01:50:10.280 --> 01:50:12.720
[Amit Varma]: We would just like them to go right.

01:50:12.720 --> 01:50:19.240
[Amit Varma]: But a modern day Tilak could make the argument that society actually agrees that free speech

01:50:19.240 --> 01:50:23.320
[Amit Varma]: should not be absolute and these laws are necessary, and that the state is absolute

01:50:23.320 --> 01:50:25.480
[Amit Varma]: and it is a crime to be against the state.

01:50:25.480 --> 01:50:29.240
[Amit Varma]: And therefore, society is not ready for these laws to go and we need these laws.

01:50:29.240 --> 01:50:30.240
[Amit Varma]: How would you respond to that?

01:50:30.240 --> 01:50:33.420
[Guest]: No, so I would say let the data speak for itself then.

01:50:33.420 --> 01:50:40.560
[Guest]: If you look at NCRB data on 124A, which they started compiling from 2014, the number of

01:50:40.560 --> 01:50:43.280
[Guest]: FIRs are measly.

01:50:43.280 --> 01:50:44.640
[Guest]: The numbers are very, very low.

01:50:44.640 --> 01:50:47.160
[Guest]: They claim there have been two convictions.

01:50:47.160 --> 01:50:49.080
[Guest]: The NCRB report claims one conviction.

01:50:49.080 --> 01:50:51.080
[Guest]: The MHA in Parliament claims two convictions.

01:50:51.080 --> 01:50:54.560
[Guest]: I haven't found even a single conviction in these two years.

01:50:54.560 --> 01:50:56.560
[Guest]: So your argument is no one is getting convicted under it?

01:50:56.560 --> 01:50:57.560
[Guest]: And the chilling effect is massive.

01:50:57.560 --> 01:50:58.880
[Guest]: The chilling effect is massive.

01:50:58.880 --> 01:51:03.680
[Guest]: So what I'm saying is today at the end of the day, in these three years now, with the

01:51:03.680 --> 01:51:09.840
[Guest]: 2017 report coming out from 2014 to 2017, only six sedition trials have been concluded.

01:51:09.840 --> 01:51:12.320
[Guest]: Only six trials have been concluded.

01:51:12.320 --> 01:51:16.160
[Guest]: And if that is the rate at which trials have been concluded and no one's been convicted

01:51:16.160 --> 01:51:20.440
[Guest]: and most cases are dying even before charge sheets are being filed, then what are you

01:51:20.440 --> 01:51:21.440
[Guest]: doing with this law?

01:51:21.440 --> 01:51:22.440
[Guest]: Why is this law in existence?

01:51:22.440 --> 01:51:25.760
[Amit Varma]: I mean, one could then argue that there are also good laws with low conviction rates.

01:51:25.760 --> 01:51:27.440
[Amit Varma]: So does that mean don't have the laws on the book?

01:51:27.440 --> 01:51:28.440
[Guest]: Could be, could be.

01:51:28.440 --> 01:51:34.160
[Guest]: But this law, when you have UAPA, when you have laws against destruction of public property,

01:51:34.160 --> 01:51:35.680
[Guest]: that is what everyone is being accused of.

01:51:35.680 --> 01:51:40.240
[Guest]: If they say violence, even the violence is only against public property, no one can overthrow

01:51:40.240 --> 01:51:41.240
[Guest]: the government.

01:51:41.240 --> 01:51:42.240
[Guest]: The government is not brittle.

01:51:42.240 --> 01:51:43.800
[Guest]: I keep saying this, that the government is not brittle today.

01:51:43.800 --> 01:51:48.040
[Guest]: So all they say is someone burnt a few buses, so convicting for sedition is not right.

01:51:48.040 --> 01:51:49.280
[Guest]: There are other laws to take care of that.

01:51:49.280 --> 01:51:54.240
[Guest]: There's laws to take care of murder, there are laws to take care of arson, of everything's

01:51:54.240 --> 01:51:55.240
[Amit Varma]: in place.

01:51:55.240 --> 01:51:56.320
[Amit Varma]: You don't need this.

01:51:56.320 --> 01:51:59.320
[Amit Varma]: So let me ask you a postscript to my final final question, which you can answer very

01:51:59.320 --> 01:52:03.440
[Amit Varma]: briefly before you run through Bombay traffic to try and get to your flight in time.

01:52:03.440 --> 01:52:04.920
[Amit Varma]: Good luck with that.

01:52:04.920 --> 01:52:10.840
[Amit Varma]: And the question is that, you know, I remember writing columns 10 years ago against 377 against

01:52:10.840 --> 01:52:15.000
[Amit Varma]: the adultery law, and they're both gone today, that you know, things evolved to a stage where

01:52:15.000 --> 01:52:19.400
[Amit Varma]: they could go naturally with no outcry and no interest groups insisting on keeping those

01:52:19.400 --> 01:52:20.400
[Amit Varma]: laws.

01:52:20.400 --> 01:52:21.400
[Amit Varma]: Are you hopeful of a time?

01:52:21.400 --> 01:52:25.360
[Amit Varma]: And if so, how long will it take that before many of these draconian laws, especially these

01:52:25.360 --> 01:52:29.560
[Amit Varma]: sort of free speech laws, and even laws like the UAPA, you know, that our society matures

01:52:29.560 --> 01:52:32.760
[Amit Varma]: enough to say that, hey, we don't need this in a healthy democracy.

01:52:32.760 --> 01:52:38.080
[Guest]: We may mature enough to say so, our political parties have to mature enough to do that.

01:52:38.080 --> 01:52:39.240
[Guest]: Is it a demand and supply?

01:52:39.240 --> 01:52:43.880
[Guest]: No, it's not really because at the end of the day, they are the ones who come to power,

01:52:43.880 --> 01:52:47.800
[Guest]: it could be a Congress, it could be a BJP, it could be a TMC, it could be anyone.

01:52:47.800 --> 01:52:49.920
[Guest]: But for them, it's a very useful tool to have.

01:52:49.920 --> 01:52:50.920
[Guest]: Why would they give it up?

01:52:50.920 --> 01:52:52.080
[Guest]: Why would they give it up?

01:52:52.080 --> 01:52:56.080
[Guest]: So it's a political party which has to mature and say, you know, I'm not afraid of this.

01:52:56.080 --> 01:52:59.480
[Guest]: So they are the ones who have to mature at the two hopeful statements were made very

01:52:59.480 --> 01:53:03.960
[Guest]: recently by two Supreme Court judges, one of whom will become the Chief Justice of India

01:53:03.960 --> 01:53:09.720
[Guest]: after the tenure of the next two and, and he says that when a cartoonist is arrested

01:53:09.720 --> 01:53:12.920
[Guest]: for sedition, the constitution weeps.

01:53:12.920 --> 01:53:19.200
[Guest]: And Justice Deepak Gupta recently gave a speech in Ahmedabad where he criticized the law of

01:53:19.200 --> 01:53:20.200
[Guest]: sedition.

01:53:20.200 --> 01:53:22.440
[Guest]: So hopeful statements are coming forward.

01:53:22.440 --> 01:53:27.440
[Guest]: But then at the same time, we have a Rajnath Singh and Amit Shah and other politicians

01:53:27.440 --> 01:53:31.760
[Guest]: of the BJP saying that this law is required and we will make it stronger.

01:53:31.760 --> 01:53:35.600
[Guest]: So that's why I'm saying people may still believe that law should go.

01:53:35.600 --> 01:53:39.280
[Guest]: It's a political parties were to be mature enough to say they're not afraid of criticism.

01:53:39.280 --> 01:53:43.200
[Guest]: They're not afraid of people saying that what you're doing is wrong.

01:53:43.200 --> 01:53:44.200
[Guest]: They have to take it sportingly.

01:53:44.200 --> 01:53:48.120
[Guest]: They know that the country cannot be overthrown by a motley group of critics.

01:53:48.120 --> 01:53:49.240
[Amit Varma]: It's as simple as that.

01:53:49.240 --> 01:53:52.640
[Amit Varma]: After doing so much to come to power, why on earth would you give some of it up?

01:53:52.640 --> 01:53:55.840
[Amit Varma]: On that hopeful note, Chitranchal, we could have spoken for hours more.

01:53:55.840 --> 01:53:57.640
[Guest]: You should have been here tomorrow morning.

01:53:57.640 --> 01:53:59.480
[Amit Varma]: Thank you so much for coming on the scene in the unseen.

01:53:59.480 --> 01:54:03.080
[Amit Varma]: Thank you so much for having me.

